        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Maragondon sits at the foot of Mount Palay-Palay in southwestern Cavite, about two and a half hours from Pasay via Kawit and Naic. Most weekenders speed past it on the way to Ternate or Nasugbu, but the town itself holds one of the most loaded sites in Philippine history. This is where the Bonifacio brothers were tried by a military court in May 1897. The trial house still stands across the plaza, and the route through it is short, walkable, and quiet on weekdays.</p>
<p>Plan it as a half-day stop, either as a morning detour before heading to Patungan or as an afternoon visit on the way back. The whole walking loop covers maybe six city blocks. Tara, here is the kwento by stop.</p>
<h2>Maragondon Church (1714)</h2>
<p>The Our Lady of the Assumption Parish is the obvious starting point. The stone facade is late baroque, the bell tower is detached from the main church, and the wooden retablo inside is one of the better preserved in southern Luzon. Mass schedules run early morning and late afternoon on weekdays; on Sundays the plaza fills up by ten in the morning. Free entry, modest dress, and the caretaker can sometimes point you to the side door if the main is locked outside of mass hours.</p>
<p>The plaza in front is the second oldest public space in Cavite after Kawit. Look for the marker stones at the corners and the small monument to General Pio del Pilar, who lived in the area before joining the Magdiwang faction.</p>
<h2>Museo ng Paglilitis ni Andres Bonifacio</h2>
<p>The trial house is a one-minute walk from the church, marked by a small brown sign. This is the Bahay na Tisa where the court martial of Andres and Procopio Bonifacio was held over five days in May 1897. The ground floor displays trial transcripts, period photographs, and a recreated session room with the original wooden floorboards. Upstairs is a small gallery on the Magdalo and Magdiwang split and the Tejeros Convention.</p>
<p>Entry is free. The caretaker gives a 20-minute guided talk if you ask. The exhibit is bilingual, mostly Tagalog with English captions. Allot 45 minutes if you read everything; 25 minutes if you walk through.</p>
<h2>Mount Nagpatong Marker</h2>
<p>The actual execution site of Andres and Procopio Bonifacio is on Mount Nagpatong, around a 30-minute habal-habal ride up from the town proper. A small concrete marker and a flagpole sit at the top, with a view of the Maragondon valley. The road is rough so most visitors skip the climb and read about it at the trial house instead. If you want to go, the habal-habal stand is across the church and the round trip including the marker stop runs around 90 minutes.</p>
<h2>Riverfront and Old Houses</h2>
<p>Walk down the main road from the trial house toward the river. The street is lined with bahay-na-bato houses from the late Spanish period, some still occupied, others slowly being absorbed by newer construction. The Maragondon River runs along the back of the town and has a small concrete walkway that the locals use for late afternoon strolls. Not a tourist setup, more of a quiet provincial scene that gives you a sense of how the town has settled into itself after 300 years.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Manila, take a Saulog Transit or San Agustin bus from Pasay or Coastal Mall bound for Ternate, and ask to be dropped at the Maragondon junction. From the junction, jeepneys and tricycles run into the town center for around 20 to 30 pesos. By car, follow the CAVITEX then Antero Soriano Highway down to Naic, then turn inland on the Maragondon-Ternate road. Travel time is two and a half to three hours from Manila depending on tollway traffic.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat</h2>
<p>Maragondon has small carinderias around the plaza serving Cavite-style adobo, pancit, and the local tinapayan. For a sit-down lunch, the eateries along the Naic road serve grilled liempo and bulalo. Pack water and small snacks if you plan to climb Nagpatong; the marker area has no vendors.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through February is the cool dry window and the best for walking around. March to May gets very hot in the open plaza. The town is busiest during the Maragondon town fiesta in August and on Bonifacio Day weekend in November, when the trial house hosts commemorative talks. Weekday mornings are the quietest, around 60 to 80 visitors a day at the museum.</p>
<p>Maragondon is the rare Cavite town where the history is still embedded in the streetscape rather than wrapped in a theme park. Walk slow, read the markers, and the place gives you more than the brochure version of 1897.</p>
