        'excerpt' => 'Ternate is the coastal end of Cavite. Here is the slow loop through Patungan Cove, Kaybiang Tunnel, and the Caleruega-style chapel road.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Ternate is the southwestern tip of Cavite, the town where the road from Manila finally meets the West Philippine Sea. It is two and a half hours from Pasay by van, three by bus and tricycle. Most weekenders pass through Ternate on the way to Nasugbu in Batangas, but the town itself holds a quiet cove, a dramatic mountain tunnel, and a chapel road that nobody talks about. This is a one-day calm drive through all three.</p>
<p>The loop works best by private car or motorbike. By public transport it is doable but slow, since the spots are spread along five kilometers of coastal road. Tara, here is the route by stop.</p>
<h2>Patungan Cove</h2>
<p>Patungan is a half-moon cove on the southern edge of Ternate, reachable by a 15-minute downhill walk from the registration area off the main road. The sand is gray-brown rather than white, and the water sits between two low headlands that block the open-sea swell. It is a swimming cove, not a surf spot. Bring your own snacks; vendor stalls are minimal.</p>
<p>The cove gets busiest on Saturdays from December to May. Tuesday and Wednesday mornings have around five to ten visitors. Day-tour fees are charged at the entrance, plus a small environmental fee for the barangay. Lifeguards are on duty during weekends only.</p>
<h2>Kaybiang Tunnel</h2>
<p>Kaybiang is the longest subterranean road tunnel in the Philippines, cutting through Mount Pico de Loro between Ternate and Nasugbu. It runs about 300 meters underground with a slight curve, and the temperature drops noticeably when you enter from the warm coastal road. Most road-trippers pull over on either end for photos. The road on the Nasugbu side opens into the Batangas coast with the Pico de Loro peak visible to the right.</p>
<p>Traffic through the tunnel runs both directions on a single carriageway, so do not stop inside. The exit pull-outs on either side are where you take the photos. Around five minutes is enough.</p>
<h2>Caylabne and the Inland Chapel</h2>
<p>Past Patungan, the road climbs into the hills above Ternate. A small chapel sits at the bend with a wooden cross and a view of the cove below. It is not a famous site, just a roadside marker that catches the late afternoon light. Locals stop to pray on Sundays and the caretaker keeps the gate open until five in the afternoon.</p>
<p>The drive continues toward Caylabne, a private resort cove on the western side of the peninsula. The public road ends at a gate; only registered guests pass through. Turn around at the gate and the loop back to the town center takes around 25 minutes.</p>
<h2>Marine Base View Point</h2>
<p>The Naval Education and Training Command sits on a hill above Ternate town. The base itself is closed to non-personnel, but the road leading up has a public turnout with a panoramic view of Manila Bay on the eastern side and the West Philippine Sea on the western. On a clear day you can see Corregidor floating in the distance. Best at golden hour, around five thirty in the afternoon.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Manila, take a Saulog or San Agustin bus from Coastal Mall bound for Ternate, around two hours including stops. From the Ternate town plaza, take a tricycle to Patungan or hire a habal-habal for the Kaybiang loop. By car, CAVITEX to Kawit, then Antero Soriano Highway down through Naic and into Ternate, around 90 to 100 kilometers from Pasay.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat</h2>
<p>Carinderias around the Ternate public market serve early lunch from ten in the morning. For seafood, the Patungan beach vendors grill the day's catch on weekends. If you cross into Nasugbu through Kaybiang, the roadside stalls past the tunnel serve fresh buko juice and grilled isaw.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through May is the dry window and the safest for the cove and the tunnel drive. June through October the road can flood near the river crossings after a typhoon. Weekday mornings are calmest. Holy Week and long weekends fill Patungan to capacity, with parking spilling onto the highway.</p>
<p>Ternate is the rare Cavite town where the coast still feels like the end of the line. The Kaybiang tunnel drive plus the Patungan cove is the easy weekend loop that does not need a Batangas detour to feel complete.</p>
