        'excerpt' => 'Tanza is a fishing town on the Manila Bay coast of Cavite. Here is the slow weekend angle covering the Sapyaw Festival, the church, and the old salt flats.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Tanza sits on the Manila Bay coast of Cavite, between Naic and Rosario. It is one of the oldest fishing towns on the bay, founded in 1666, and the local economy still runs on the morning catch and the salt flats that line the shore. Most weekend traffic skips Tanza on the way to Ternate, but the town has a calm festival weekend, a stone church, and a coastline that is honest rather than scenic. This is a slow two-day plan for a real Cavite read.</p>
<p>The town center is small. The salt flats and fish pens sit along Manila Bay to the north. Tara, here is the weekend by stop.</p>
<h2>Day One: Town Center and the Church</h2>
<p>Holy Cross Parish in the Tanza plaza dates to 1786, rebuilt several times after earthquakes. The facade is plain late baroque, plastered white, and the bell tower carries a working bronze bell that rings the angelus at noon and six in the evening. Mass schedules run weekdays at six in the morning, Sundays at five thirty and seven. The plaza around it is a typical Cavite town setup: a small gazebo, mango trees, and benches.</p>
<p>From the plaza, walk three blocks toward the public market. The Tanza wet market handles the morning catch from the bay and stays loud from four to nine in the morning. Galunggong, hasa-hasa, tahong, and the local talangka are the staples. Pick up a kilo of fresh tahong to bring home if you have a cooler.</p>
<h2>Sapyaw Festival</h2>
<p>The Sapyaw Festival happens every May 3 around the Feast of the Holy Cross. Sapyaw refers to the traditional fishing net the Tanza fishermen used before motorized boats. The festival opens with a fluvial procession on Manila Bay, where decorated boats sail from the Tanza shore back to the parish. A street dance follows in the afternoon along the main road, with the local elementary and high school students performing.</p>
<p>The whole event runs from morning to early evening. Vendors line the plaza with grilled tuyo and rice cakes; the church holds a thanksgiving mass at four in the afternoon. If you cannot make it in May, the smaller weekly fluvial blessings on Saturday afternoons during summer are a quieter version of the same scene.</p>
<h2>Salt Flats and the Bay Coast</h2>
<p>North of the town center, the road opens to the Tanza salt flats. From November to April, the flats are at full evaporation season, and the salt farmers harvest in shallow basins lined with bamboo. The walk along the dike road takes around 40 minutes one way and the late afternoon light hits the flats from the west. This is not a developed tourist spot, just a working salt farm where locals tolerate visitors who do not interrupt the harvest.</p>
<p>The Tanza fishing port sits at the end of the same road. The morning boats unload between four and seven in the morning, the afternoon boats between three and five. Buy directly from the boat owners if you want the freshest fish; the price runs about half of the wet market rate.</p>
<h2>Day Two: Old Houses and the River Walk</h2>
<p>Tanza has a few surviving bahay-na-bato houses on Calle Real and the streets near the church. Most are private residences and not open to visitors, but you can walk past them on a 30-minute heritage loop. The Tanza River runs along the western edge of the town and has a small bridge that crosses into Naic. The river walk is short, around 15 minutes, and ends at a small viewpoint over the bay.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Pasay or Baclaran, take a San Agustin or Saulog bus bound for Naic and ask to be dropped at the Tanza junction, around 90 minutes. From the junction, tricycles run to the plaza in 10 minutes. By car, CAVITEX to Kawit then Antero Soriano Highway, around 65 kilometers from Pasay.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat</h2>
<p>The carinderias around the public market open by six in the morning. Order the tinapa and rice for breakfast, the inihaw na bangus and pinakbet for lunch. For a sit-down meal, the eateries along the Antero Soriano Highway near the Tanza exit serve bulalo and crispy pata.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through April is the dry window. The Sapyaw Festival on May 3 is the headline weekend. The smaller Saturday fluvials run from December to May. Avoid June through October if you want to walk the salt flats; the rains flood the dike road.</p>
<p>Tanza is the kind of Cavite town that does not market itself, but rewards the calm visitor with a real fishing-village rhythm. Walk the plaza, watch the boats unload, and the town stops feeling like a stopover.</p>
