        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Real is the small coastal town of Quezon Province that faces the Pacific Ocean, around four hours from Quezon City via Antipolo and Tanay. It is the closest open-ocean surf coast to Manila, closer than Baler by about two hours of drive time, and the local surf community has been quietly building since the early 2000s. Most beginner surfers from Manila skip Real for La Union, but the waves here are honest and the crowds are thinner. This is a calm weekend plan for the surf strip and the nearby beaches.</p>
<p>The town center sits on the main road, and the surf-friendly stretch runs from Brgy Ungos to Brgy Tignoan, about 12 kilometers of coast. Tara, here is the weekend by day.</p>
<h2>Day One: The Drive and Ungos Beach</h2>
<p>The drive from Manila runs through Marcos Highway in Antipolo, up the Sierra Madre, then down through Infanta to Real. Plan to leave Manila by six in the morning to clear the Antipolo traffic. The Sierra Madre stretch has 30 kilometers of mountain switchbacks and a few small waterfalls along the road. Stop at the Real-Infanta viewpoint at the top of the pass for the Pacific overlook.</p>
<p>Arrive in Real by lunchtime. Brgy Ungos is the main surf beach. The break is a beach break with both left and right peaks, beginner-friendly during the smaller season from April to October, more advanced from November to March when typhoon swells come through. Surf schools cluster at the north end of Ungos beach. Two-hour beginner lessons are available year-round.</p>
<h2>Day One Afternoon: Surf Lesson and Sunset</h2>
<p>Book a two-hour lesson with one of the Ungos surf instructors. Beginner sessions teach you the pop-up, the paddle, and the basic stance on a soft-top board. Real waves are gentler than La Union in the calmer months, which makes the learning curve forgiving. Sunset on the Pacific side faces inland, so the actual color show is on the western sky behind you, but the eastern horizon turns soft pink as the sun sets behind the Sierra Madre.</p>
<h2>Day Two: Tignoan Beach and the Quiet Side</h2>
<p>Tignoan is 15 minutes south of Ungos, a longer and quieter beach with fewer surfers. The waves here run smaller and the beach is wider, good for walking and for kids who want to play in the shore break. A small bamboo restaurant at the south end serves grilled fish and rice for lunch. After lunch, walk the length of the beach, around 30 minutes one way.</p>
<p>On the way back to the town center, stop at the Real public market. The morning catch arrives around five and runs out by ten. Pick up tamban and lapu-lapu if you want to bring fish home; the price is around two-thirds of the Manila wet market rate.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Cubao, Raymond Transportation runs the Manila-Real-Infanta route with the first bus leaving at five in the morning. Travel time is four to five hours including the mountain climb. By car, take Marcos Highway through Cogeo and Antipolo, then follow the signs for Infanta. The road is paved but narrow and has sharp turns past Sampaloc, Tanay.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat</h2>
<p>The carinderias along the main road in Real town serve early breakfast from five in the morning. Tapsilog, longsilog, and the local laing made from fresh gabi leaves are the regular orders. For dinner, the beach-side eateries in Ungos grill fresh tuna and tanigue. The portions are large; one order feeds two.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>April through October is the small-wave season, best for first-timers. November through March is the bigger-wave season for intermediate surfers. The Pacific coast gets the brunt of typhoons from June to October, so check the weather two days ahead. Avoid Holy Week if you want the surf strip uncrowded; the Manila surfers come down in force.</p>
<p>Real is the Quezon coast that absorbs Manila weekenders without losing its small-town pace. Two days is enough to learn the basics, eat a few fish meals, and get the Sierra Madre drive out of your system.</p>
