        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Infanta is the larger sister town of Real, sitting on the same Pacific coast of Quezon Province but with a wider river mouth, a longer beachfront, and an older town center. Most surfers go straight to Real for the waves and skip Infanta, but the town itself holds the older church, the Agos River delta, and a calmer beach scene. This is a diy weekend plan for the quieter Pacific side.</p>
<p>Infanta is around 30 minutes north of Real along the same coastal road. Tara, here is the loop by stop.</p>
<h2>Saint Mark the Evangelist Cathedral</h2>
<p>The Infanta cathedral was built in 1894 and serves as the seat of the Prelature of Infanta. The facade is plain colonial, plastered cream, and the interior holds a wooden retablo and the original stone altar. The cathedral plaza is the largest public space in town, and Sunday mornings see the whole local population pass through. Free entry, modest dress, weekday mass at six in the morning.</p>
<p>The old convento beside the cathedral now houses a small museum on the history of the prelature and the 2004 typhoon that flooded the lowlands of Infanta. The display includes period photographs and the names of the parishioners lost in the disaster. Around 20 minutes is enough.</p>
<h2>Agos River and the Delta</h2>
<p>The Agos River runs through the western edge of Infanta and meets the Pacific at a wide delta. The river mouth is a calm walking spot, especially at low tide when the sand bars are exposed. Bring a sun hat and water; the delta has no shade. Walk along the east bank for around 20 minutes to reach the river mouth proper. The Pacific opens up to the right and the Sierra Madre rises behind you.</p>
<p>Local fishermen launch from the delta at dawn and return by mid-morning. The catch is sold at the public market in town. If you want to ride a small banca across the river to the western bank, the fare is around 20 pesos and the crossing takes five minutes.</p>
<h2>Dinahican Beach</h2>
<p>Dinahican is the long sandy stretch on the southern edge of Infanta. The sand is darker than the white-beach typical of Visayas, and the waves are similar to Real, around shoulder-high in the small season. A few small surf shops rent boards by the hour for around 200 pesos. The beach is rarely crowded on weekdays.</p>
<p>The southern end of Dinahican has a small fishing hamlet where the locals dry tuyo on bamboo racks. Walk past at sunrise and the whole beach smells of salt and smoke. A few carinderias serve breakfast tapsilog and grilled tilapia by the beach.</p>
<h2>Public Market and the Local Food</h2>
<p>The Infanta public market is the regional hub for the Sierra Madre side. Vendors come down from the inland villages on Saturday mornings with mountain vegetables, wild honey, and free-range chicken. The market opens at four in the morning. Buy a kilo of fresh espasol or sapin-sapin from the rice cake vendors on the corner.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Cubao, Raymond Transportation runs buses to Infanta with the first leaving at five in the morning. Travel time is around four and a half hours. By car, the route is the same as Real: Marcos Highway, Antipolo, Sampaloc, then the Sierra Madre descent. Total around 150 kilometers from Cubao.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>Infanta has small lodging houses near the public market and a few beach-side cottages along Dinahican. The town does not have large resort developments, which is part of what keeps it quiet. Book ahead during Holy Week and the December break.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through May is the dry window. June through October is typhoon season on the Pacific side, with the heaviest rains in August and September. The town floods occasionally during major typhoons, so check the weather and avoid the wet months if it is your first visit.</p>
<p>Infanta is the slower Pacific town that gives you the same Sierra Madre drive without the surf-strip crowd. Walk the delta, eat at the carinderias, and the trip starts to feel like a real provincial weekend.</p>
