        'title' => 'Atimonan Quezon: The Bitukang Manok Zigzag Drive',
        'slug' => 'atimonan-quezon-bitukang-manok-zigzag-drive',
        'excerpt' => 'Atimonan sits on the eastern coast of Quezon Province. Here is the slow drive plan covering the zigzag road, the old church, and the Pacific shore.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Atimonan is the coastal town of Quezon Province where the Maharlika Highway hits the Pacific Ocean. It is the gateway town for the long drive south to Bicol, and the local landmark is the Bitukang Manok, the chicken-intestine zigzag road that winds through the Quezon National Park between Pagbilao and Atimonan. This is a slow drive plan covering the zigzag, the town center, and the eastern beach.</p>
<p>Atimonan sits around four and a half hours from Manila via SLEX and the Maharlika. Tara, here is the loop by stop.</p>
<h2>Bitukang Manok Zigzag Road</h2>
<p>The Bitukang Manok is the old colonial road that climbs through the Quezon National Park, around 14 kilometers of switchbacks and steep turns. The road was the only land route to Bicol before the modern Maharlika bypass opened. The forest along the route still holds tall hardwood trees and an active wildlife corridor; you might spot a flying lemur if you stop quietly at dusk.</p>
<p>Most modern drivers take the bypass and skip the old road, but the zigzag is still drivable and is the more scenic option. Plan around 45 minutes to drive the full length. The road has a few small viewpoints near the top of the pass where you can pull over for photos of the Pacific coast below.</p>
<h2>Quezon National Park</h2>
<p>The park has a small picnic area near the summit of the zigzag with cement tables and a covered shelter. A short walking trail leads to a viewpoint over the forest canopy. Around 20 minutes is enough. The park rangers are friendly and can point you to the longer trails if you want a half-day hike instead.</p>
<h2>Atimonan Town Center</h2>
<p>The Atimonan church is the Saint Hyacinth Parish, rebuilt in the 19th century after the original 1606 structure was damaged. The facade is plain late baroque with a single bell tower. The plaza in front is the town center and the locals gather in the late afternoon for chess matches and merienda. The public market is one block away and serves the freshest catch from the Atimonan coast.</p>
<p>Walk three blocks east from the plaza to the Atimonan coast. The beach here is darker sand, the waves are bigger than Manila Bay, and the view east opens to the Pacific. Local fishermen launch from the small jetty at the south end of the beach. Sunrise is the best window, around five thirty in the morning.</p>
<h2>Eastern Beaches</h2>
<p>The town has a few small beachfront cottages along the southern coast toward Plaridel. The sand is gray, the water is clear past the wave break, and the area is rarely crowded. A short walk south leads to a small headland with a view of the bay. Plan around two hours for a beach walk and a swim.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Cubao, JAC Liner and DLTBCo run buses to Atimonan with the first leaving at four in the morning. Travel time is around five hours via SLEX and Maharlika. By car, take SLEX to STAR Tollway, then the Maharlika south through Tiaong, Candelaria, Sariaya, and Lucena. Total around 180 kilometers.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat</h2>
<p>Atimonan has a few well-known stops along the Maharlika that bus passengers know by name. Buko pie and longganisa are the takeaway items. For sit-down meals, the carinderias around the public market serve sinigang na bangus, ginataang gulay, and the local lambanog if you want a small shot. Lambanog from Atimonan is one of the stronger varieties in Luzon.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through May is the dry window. June through October the eastern coast gets the brunt of typhoons. The Bitukang Manok road is safer in the dry months; landslides can close sections during heavy rain. Avoid Holy Week if you want the road traffic light; the Bicol-bound buses jam the highway.</p>
<p>Atimonan is the calm midpoint between Manila and Bicol that most travelers blow through. Stop, drive the zigzag, eat the bangus sinigang, and the town gives you a real sense of the old Maharlika before it became a tollway.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Atimonan Quezon: The Bitukang Manok Zigzag Drive | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A slow Atimonan Quezon plan covering the Bitukang Manok zigzag road, the national park, the old church plaza, and the eastern Pacific beach.',
        'tags' => 'Quezon Province, Atimonan, Zigzag Road, Road Trip',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'quezon-province',
    ],

