    // 7. PADRE BURGOS BORAWAN DAMPALITAN COMBO
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.escapemanila.com/2019/03/best-beaches-in-quezon-province.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'EscapeManila',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Padre Burgos Quezon: Borawan and Dampalitan Beach Combo',
        'slug' => 'padre-burgos-quezon-borawan-dampalitan-beach-combo',
        'excerpt' => 'Padre Burgos is the gateway to Borawan and Dampalitan island camping. Here is the slow weekend plan for the two-beach Quezon combo.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Padre Burgos is a small coastal town on the southwestern tip of Quezon Province, around five hours from Manila via SLEX, STAR, and the Maharlika. It is the launch point for two of the calmest island beaches in southern Luzon: Borawan, with its limestone formations and white-coral sand, and Dampalitan, a longer white-sand stretch with shade from old talisay trees. This is the slow weekend plan covering both islands.</p>
<p>The town center is small and the boat launch is a short tricycle ride away. Tara, here is the weekend by day.</p>
<h2>Day One: The Drive and the Boat Launch</h2>
<p>Plan to leave Manila by five in the morning. The Maharlika south of Lucena slows down on weekends, so the early start matters. Stop at Sariaya for the panciteria and the old houses if you have a 30-minute buffer. From Lucena, take the southbound route through Pagbilao and Padre Burgos, around 90 minutes more. The boat launch at Brgy Bantigue is well-marked.</p>
<p>Negotiate the boat rate at the launch. The standard package covers the round trip to Borawan and Dampalitan and back to Bantigue. Day trippers pay one rate; overnight campers pay the same for transport plus the island camping fees. The boat ride takes around 30 minutes one way to either island.</p>
<h2>Borawan Island</h2>
<p>Borawan is the smaller island, named for its resemblance to Boracay in miniature, though the actual landscape is different. The beach is short, around 200 meters, with white-coral sand and the limestone cliffs that frame it on both ends. The water is calm and clear, with snorkeling visibility around three meters. Bring your own gear; the island rentals are basic.</p>
<p>The island has a small day-use fee and camping is allowed on the southern end. No commercial vendors, so bring all your food, water, and trash bags. Plan around two hours if you are day-tripping, six hours if you swim and lunch.</p>
<h2>Day Two: Dampalitan Island</h2>
<p>Dampalitan is the longer island, around one kilometer of white sand fringed by old talisay trees that provide natural shade. The water is shallower than Borawan, calm enough for kids, with a sandbar that extends at low tide. The eastern end has small tide pools with reef fish. Walk the length of the beach at sunrise, around 40 minutes one way.</p>
<p>Camping is allowed and most overnight visitors prefer Dampalitan over Borawan for the shade and the longer beach. Bring your own tent or rent from the boat operators. Toilet facilities are basic. The boat back to Bantigue runs by mid-afternoon, in time for the drive back to Manila by evening.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Cubao, take a JAC Liner bus bound for Lucena, then a smaller bus or van bound for Padre Burgos. Total travel time is around six hours one way. By car, take SLEX to STAR, then Maharlika south through Sariaya, Lucena, Pagbilao, and Padre Burgos. The road is paved all the way.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<p>Bring all your food and water from Lucena or Manila. The islands have no stores. Tent, sleeping mat, basic cooking gear, and a power bank if you are camping overnight. Insect repellent is essential, especially at Dampalitan where the talisay trees host sand flies at dusk.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>March through May is the dry window and the calmest sea. June through October has typhoon swells that can cancel boat trips. December through February is dry but the northeast monsoon can choppy the sea, so check the forecast two days ahead. Avoid Holy Week if you want the islands quiet; both fill to capacity.</p>
<p>Padre Burgos is the calmer Quezon weekend that gives you two distinct island feels in 36 hours. Borawan for the cliffs, Dampalitan for the shade, and the drive back through Lucena for the longganisa.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Padre Burgos Quezon: Borawan and Dampalitan Beach Combo | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A slow Padre Burgos Quezon weekend covering Borawan limestone cove, Dampalitan talisay shade, the boat launch, and camping tips. DIY notes.',
        'tags' => 'Quezon Province, Padre Burgos, Borawan, Dampalitan, Camping',
