    // 8. GUMACA QUEZON ARANA AT BALUARTE
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.escapemanila.com/2019/03/top-tourist-spots-in-quezon-province.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'EscapeManila',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Gumaca Quezon: The Arana at Baluarte Festival Weekend',
        'slug' => 'gumaca-quezon-arana-baluarte-festival-weekend',
        'excerpt' => 'Gumaca is a coastal town of Quezon Province with a unique May festival. Here is the slow weekend plan for Arana at Baluarte and the old church.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Gumaca is a coastal town on the eastern side of Quezon Province, around six hours from Manila by bus. It is one of the older towns in southern Luzon, founded in 1582, and the local landmark is the Arana at Baluarte, a folk dance and parade held every May 15 for the feast of Saint Isidore the Farmer. The town is rarely on the standard Quezon itinerary, but the festival weekend and the older heritage make it worth the slower trip.</p>
<p>The town center is small and the festival activities cluster around the plaza and the old church. Tara, here is the weekend by day.</p>
<h2>Day One: Arrival and the Old Church</h2>
<p>The Saint Diego de Alcala Church in Gumaca was first built in 1685 and rebuilt several times after earthquakes and fires. The current structure is from the late 19th century with a plain stone facade and a single bell tower. The interior holds a wooden retablo with the image of Saint Diego and the side altar of Saint Isidore. The plaza in front is the festival grounds.</p>
<p>Walk three blocks east from the plaza to the public market. The Gumaca market handles the morning catch from the bay and the inland produce from the Sierra Madre side. Vendors come down from Lopez and Calauag with mountain bananas, coconuts, and root crops. The market opens at four in the morning.</p>
<h2>Arana at Baluarte Festival</h2>
<p>The Arana at Baluarte runs every May 14 to 15. The Arana is the spider, represented by performers dressed in elaborate spider costumes who move through the streets in slow choreography. The Baluarte is the bamboo tower carrying offerings of vegetables, rice, and the local kakanin, paraded through town as a thanksgiving for the harvest. The festival ends with a mass at the church and a community meal where the offerings are distributed.</p>
<p>The whole event runs from morning to evening on May 15. The streets fill by midmorning and the procession starts at one in the afternoon. The performers wear hand-made costumes from the local barangays, each with its own variation. Bring a small camera; the spider costumes are the photogenic part.</p>
<h2>Day Two: Coast and the Slow Side</h2>
<p>The Gumaca coast faces Lamon Bay and the open Pacific. The beach south of the town center is fishing village rather than tourist beach, but the early morning scene of boats coming in with the catch is one of the calmer provincial reads in southern Luzon. Walk the dirt path along the shore for around 30 minutes one way. The fishermen are friendly and will sell you direct from the boat if you bring a cooler.</p>
<p>For the inland angle, hire a tricycle to the Suplay Falls in the foothills, around 30 minutes from the town center. The falls is small, around five meters, but the pool is wide and the surrounding bamboo grove keeps the area cool. A small registration fee at the trailhead, and the walk in from the parking is around 15 minutes.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Cubao, DLTBCo and JAC Liner run buses to Gumaca with first departures at four in the morning. Travel time is around six hours via SLEX and Maharlika. By car, the route is the same as Atimonan; Gumaca is around 40 minutes further south.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat</h2>
<p>The carinderias around the Gumaca plaza serve early breakfast from five in the morning. Sinigang na bangus, ginataang ubod, and the local kakanin are the regular orders. The Gumaca empanada is a small fried turnover filled with pork and chayote, sold by vendors near the church for merienda.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through May is the dry window. The Arana at Baluarte on May 15 is the headline weekend. The smaller harvest blessings on Saturday afternoons during summer are quieter alternatives. Avoid June through October if you want to walk the coast; the rains flood the lowland roads.</p>
<p>Gumaca is the older Quezon town that absorbs the bus crowd without becoming a tourist stop. Walk the plaza, watch the spider parade, and the town gives you a Luzon weekend that does not feel like a copy of Sariaya or Lucban.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Gumaca Quezon: The Arana at Baluarte Festival Weekend | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm Gumaca Quezon weekend covering the Arana at Baluarte festival, the 1685 church, the public market, and Suplay Falls. DIY notes from Manila.',
        'tags' => 'Quezon Province, Gumaca, Arana at Baluarte, Festival, Heritage',
