    // 10. MANGATAREM PANGASINAN MANLELUAG SPRING PARK
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.escapemanila.com/2019/02/top-tourist-spots-in-pangasinan.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'EscapeManila',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Mangatarem Pangasinan: Manleluag Spring Park Day Trip',
        'slug' => 'mangatarem-pangasinan-manleluag-spring-park-day-trip',
        'excerpt' => 'Mangatarem sits inland from the Pangasinan coast. Here is the day-trip plan for Manleluag Spring Park, the warm pools, and the surrounding forest.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Mangatarem is a small inland town in western Pangasinan, around 30 minutes east of Aguilar. Most travelers skip it entirely on the way to Bolinao or Hundred Islands, but the town holds the Manleluag Spring Protected Landscape, a 1,800-hectare reserve with natural sulfur warm springs, a forest reserve, and easy walking trails. This is a day-trip plan for the spring park and the Mangatarem town center.</p>
<p>The park sits around 20 minutes east of the town proper. Tara, here is the day by stop.</p>
<h2>Manleluag Spring Park</h2>
<p>The park's main feature is a series of warm sulfur pools fed by underground springs from the foothills of the Zambales mountain range. The water temperature ranges from 38 to 42 degrees Celsius, and the largest pool can fit around 30 visitors at one time. The locals attribute therapeutic properties to the sulfur, especially for skin conditions and muscle soreness. Whether or not that holds up scientifically, the warm soak after a long drive feels good.</p>
<p>Entry fees are modest. The park has cottages around the pool area for groups and a small canteen serving snacks and rice meals. Bring your own swimwear, towel, and water. The pools are open from seven in the morning to five in the afternoon, no overnight stays.</p>
<h2>Forest Trail</h2>
<p>A short forest trail starts at the park entrance and winds through second-growth tropical forest for around 45 minutes round trip. The trail is well-marked and easy, suitable for kids and elders. Birds are common; the local barangay rangers report sightings of hornbills and kingfishers. Bring insect repellent.</p>
<p>The trail ends at a small lookout point with a view of the Mangatarem valley and the Zambales mountains to the west. Plan around two hours total if you walk the trail and soak at the pool.</p>
<h2>Mangatarem Town Center</h2>
<p>Drive back to the town center for late lunch. The Mangatarem church is the Saint Joseph the Worker Parish, a 19th-century stone building with a wide plaza. The public market is one block away and serves the inland produce from the foothills: mountain bananas, coconuts, and root crops. Vendors also sell the local kakanin and tikoy.</p>
<p>Walk the plaza for 20 minutes. The town hall sits on the western side and the streets around it have a few old commercial buildings from the early 20th century.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Cubao or Pasay, Victory Liner runs buses to Dagupan or Urdaneta. From either, take a jeepney bound for Mangatarem, around 90 minutes. Total travel time is around six hours. By car, NLEX to TPLEX to the Urdaneta exit, then the inland highway west to Mangatarem.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat</h2>
<p>The carinderias around the town plaza serve early breakfast and rice meals all day. Bagoong-flavored bangus, dinengdeng, and the local pakbet are the regular orders. For a sit-down lunch, the eateries near the public market serve crispy pata and bulalo.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November through May is the dry window. The pools are busiest during the summer months from March to May. Weekday mornings rarely have more than 50 visitors at the park. Avoid Holy Week if you want the pools quiet; the local crowd fills the cottages by noon.</p>
<p>Mangatarem is the rare Pangasinan town that gives you a warm-spring soak without the long drive to Pansol. Combine it with a Bolinao or Alaminos overnight if you want a longer weekend, or do it as a one-day side trip from Dagupan.</p>
