    // 11. TONDOL BEACH ANDA PANGASINAN
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.escapemanila.com/2019/03/best-beaches-in-pangasinan.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'EscapeManila',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Tondol Beach Anda Pangasinan: The Low-Tide Sandbar Walk',
        'slug' => 'tondol-beach-anda-pangasinan-low-tide-sandbar-walk',
        'excerpt' => 'Tondol Beach in Anda Pangasinan has a long sandbar at low tide. Here is the diy day-trip plan for the walk and the surrounding fishing village.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Tondol Beach sits on the northern tip of Anda Island in western Pangasinan, a 90-minute drive from Bolinao or Alaminos. It is the rare Luzon beach with a tide pattern that drops the sea level enough to expose a one-kilometer sandbar at low tide. Walk out at the right hour and you are knee-deep in calm water with the South China Sea on both sides. Most weekenders pass Anda for Bolinao, but Tondol is a quieter alternative for a day trip or an overnight.</p>
<p>The beach sits at the end of a 20-minute drive from the Anda town proper. Tara, here is the day by stop.</p>
<h2>Tondol Beach Arrival</h2>
<p>The beach is fronted by a row of small cottages run by local families. Day-use fees are modest, parking is on the sand under shade trees, and the cottage rentals come with a basic table and bamboo benches. No big resorts, no commercial vendors. Bring your own food and water from Anda town.</p>
<p>The sand is white and powdery, the beach is around 600 meters long, and the water at high tide is waist-deep up to about 50 meters out. The real spectacle is at low tide.</p>
<h2>The Sandbar Walk</h2>
<p>Check the local tide chart before you go. The sandbar emerges around two hours before low tide and stays exposed for around three hours. The bar runs roughly northwest from the main beach toward a small islet, around one kilometer in length. The water on both sides is shallow, around ankle to knee depth, and the bottom is firm sand with no sharp rocks.</p>
<p>Walk slow, watch for small reef fish and starfish in the tide pools, and stop at the islet at the end. Bring water shoes if you have sensitive feet. The walk back to the main beach takes around 25 minutes.</p>
<h2>Anda Town and the Fishing Village</h2>
<p>Drive back to the Anda town center for late lunch. The town has a small public market, a church plaza, and a few carinderias. The Anda church is the Saint Vincent Ferrer Parish, a modest stone building from the 19th century. The locals are friendly and the pace is slow.</p>
<p>The fishing village south of the town has small bancas pulled up on the sand and racks of drying tuyo. Walk past in the late afternoon for the smoke-and-salt scene that is typical of the Pangasinan coast.</p>
<h2>Overnight Option</h2>
<p>If you stay overnight, the Tondol cottages offer basic sleeping mats and pillows. Tents are also allowed on the beach for an additional fee. Bring your own bedding if you want comfort. Toilet and shower facilities are basic.</p>
<p>The overnight stay gives you the sunset on the western horizon and the early morning low tide for the sandbar walk before the day visitors arrive.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Cubao, Victory Liner runs buses to Alaminos. From Alaminos, take a van or jeepney bound for Anda. Travel time is around six and a half hours one way. By car, NLEX to TPLEX to Urdaneta, then the coastal highway through Alaminos and Bani, and across the short bridge to Anda Island.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November through May is the dry window. The sandbar appears year-round at low tide, but the calmer dry months are best for the walk and the swim. Avoid July through September; the southwest monsoon roughens the sea. Check the tide chart at <a href="https://www.tide-forecast.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">tide-forecast.com</a> before you go.</p>
<p>Tondol Beach is the Pangasinan beach that rewards the slow visitor. Time the tide right, walk the bar, and the trip becomes the quiet alternative to the Hundred Islands weekend.</p>
