        'title' => 'Cabongaoan Beach Burgos Pangasinan: The Death Pool Weekend',
        'slug' => 'cabongaoan-beach-burgos-pangasinan-death-pool-weekend',
        'excerpt' => 'Cabongaoan Beach in Burgos Pangasinan has the famous Death Pool tidal feature. Here is the diy weekend plan for the rock formation and the white sand.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Cabongaoan Beach sits on the western coast of Burgos, Pangasinan, around an hour north of Bolinao. The town is small and the beach is rarely on the standard Pangasinan itinerary, but it holds one of the more unusual coastal features in northern Luzon: the Death Pool, a natural rock basin that fills with seawater at high tide and forms a deep swimming hole rimmed by sharp limestone. This is the diy weekend plan for the beach and the rock formation.</p>
<p>Burgos is around 90 minutes by tricycle from Bolinao town proper. Tara, here is the weekend by day.</p>
<h2>Day One: Cabongaoan Beach</h2>
<p>The main beach at Cabongaoan is a 600-meter stretch of white sand, less developed than Patar in Bolinao and rarely crowded. Day-use fees are modest, cottages are run by local families, and the food options are basic. Bring your own snacks and water.</p>
<p>The water is calm in the morning and choppy by mid-afternoon during the southwest monsoon. Swimming is safe near the shore but the locals advise against going past 50 meters from the beach, especially during the wet season when underwater currents pick up.</p>
<h2>The Death Pool</h2>
<p>The Death Pool sits at the northern end of the beach, around a 10-minute walk along the rocky coast. The pool is a natural basin around 15 meters wide and four meters deep at high tide, fed by the rising sea through a narrow channel. The name is misleading; the pool is a calm swimming spot, not a hazard, but the surrounding limestone is sharp and the channel into the sea has stronger currents during heavy swells.</p>
<p>Climb down the rocks carefully. The pool water is clear and the bottom is sand. Locals jump from the higher rocks around the rim, around three meters above the water, but check the depth first. Stay out of the channel that connects the pool to the sea; the currents there can pull you out.</p>
<h2>Day Two: The Cape Bolinao Side</h2>
<p>Drive back south toward Bolinao for the second day. Stop at the Cape Bolinao Lighthouse on the way for the view over the coast. The lighthouse is a 19th-century stone tower that still operates, and the climb to the top gives you the best view of the Patar coast and the South China Sea horizon.</p>
<p>For lunch, drive into Patar village and stop at one of the carinderias serving fresh seafood. Grilled tuna, kinilaw, and the local sinigang are the regular orders.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Cubao, Victory Liner runs buses to Alaminos. From Alaminos, take a van or jeepney to Bolinao, then a tricycle to Burgos and Cabongaoan. Total travel time is around eight hours one way. By car, NLEX to TPLEX to Urdaneta, then the coastal highway through Alaminos and Bolinao, then north to Burgos.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat</h2>
<p>The carinderias near the Cabongaoan beach entrance serve simple rice meals. For a more reliable meal, drive back to Bolinao town for the eateries near the church plaza. Pamulinawen restaurant serves Ilocano staples and the local seafood specialties.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November through May is the dry window. The Death Pool is best at high tide, around two hours before and after, when the water level is deepest and the channel is calm. Check the local tide chart before you go. Avoid the southwest monsoon months from July to September; the swells make the pool dangerous.</p>
<p>Cabongaoan is the rare Pangasinan beach where the feature is geological rather than recreational. Walk slow, time the tide, and the Death Pool stops feeling like a tourist gimmick and starts feeling like a coastal oddity worth the long drive.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Cabongaoan Beach Burgos Pangasinan: The Death Pool Weekend | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A weekend plan for Cabongaoan Beach in Burgos Pangasinan, covering the Death Pool tidal basin, the white sand stretch, and the Cape Bolinao side.',
        'tags' => 'Pangasinan, Burgos, Cabongaoan Beach, Death Pool, Weekend',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'pangasinan-general',
