        'title' => 'Bacnotan La Union: Pebble Beach and the Northern Quiet Side',
        'slug' => 'bacnotan-la-union-pebble-beach-northern-quiet-side',
        'excerpt' => 'Bacnotan is the northernmost town of La Union. Here is the slow weekend plan for Pebble Beach, the local market, and the inland barangays.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Bacnotan sits at the northern edge of La Union, the last town before you cross into Ilocos Sur. Most surfers stop at San Juan and skip Bacnotan entirely, but the town has a quiet pebble beach, a small heritage church, and a coastal road that gives you the calmest side of La Union. This is a slow weekend plan for the pebble coast and the town proper.</p>
<p>Bacnotan is around 25 minutes north of San Fernando by jeepney. Tara, here is the weekend by day.</p>
<h2>Day One: Pebble Beach</h2>
<p>The Bacnotan coast is mostly pebbled rather than sandy, a long stretch of smooth gray stones polished by the South China Sea. The locals call it Pebble Beach informally, and a few sections have small patches of sand near the river mouths. The pebbles make for a different beach feel; walking barefoot is uncomfortable but the sound of the surf rolling over the stones is calming.</p>
<p>The best stretch is around Barangay Baroro near the bridge over the river. Park at the small turnout and walk down the embankment to the beach. The waves break harder here than in San Juan and swimming is not recommended; this is a walking and sitting beach, not a swim beach. Late afternoon light hits the western horizon around five thirty.</p>
<h2>Day One Afternoon: Town Center</h2>
<p>The Bacnotan church is the Saint John the Baptist Parish, a 19th-century stone structure with a plain facade and a single bell tower. The plaza in front is the town center and the locals gather in the late afternoon for chess and merienda. The public market is two blocks away and serves the regional produce: garlic from Vigan, tomatoes from the inland barangays, and the local fresh catch.</p>
<p>Walk past the Don Mariano Marcos State University campus on the way out of town. The university grounds are large and the old buildings from the 1950s still stand, with mango trees lining the main road.</p>
<h2>Day Two: Inland Barangays and Baroro River</h2>
<p>Hire a tricycle or rent a bike for a half-day inland loop. The barangays of San Aurelio and Casiaman sit in the foothills of the Cordillera and the road winds through rice terraces and small streams. Stop at the Baroro Riverside for a calm morning walk; the river runs clear and shallow with smooth rocks along the bank.</p>
<p>The inland villages are mostly farming communities. The locals are friendly and will point you to small swimming holes along the river if you ask. Bring water and a small snack; no commercial vendors along the route.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Cubao or Pasay, take a Partas or Genesis bus bound for Vigan and ask to be dropped at Bacnotan. Travel time is around six hours. From San Juan or San Fernando, jeepneys run north every 15 minutes during daylight hours. By car, TPLEX to Rosario, then Manila North Road north through San Fernando to Bacnotan.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat</h2>
<p>The carinderias around the Bacnotan plaza serve early breakfast and rice meals. Order the Ilocos longganisa with garlic rice for breakfast, the bagnet with KBL (kamatis-bagoong-lasona) for lunch. The local panaderia near the church sells the regional empanada and bibingka.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through May is the dry window. June through October is the wet season and the coastal road floods near the river crossings. Sundays and Holy Week fill the town center with the local fiesta crowd, but the pebble beach stays quiet year-round.</p>
<p>Bacnotan is the La Union town that does not pull weekenders and quietly rewards the ones who show up. Walk the pebble coast, eat at the carinderias, and the trip becomes the calm northern bookend to a Pagudpud or Vigan road trip.</p>
