<p>Caba is one of the smaller La Union towns, sitting between Aringay and Bauang on the southern coastal stretch. The town center holds a 19th-century church and a small plaza, and the coast has a series of small coves and fishing villages that most beachgoers skip on the way to Bauang or San Juan. This is a slow weekend ride for the south La Union coast.</p>
<p>Caba is around 20 minutes south of San Fernando by car. Tara, here is the weekend by day.</p>
<h2>Day One: Liguay Cove</h2>
<p>Liguay is a small cove on the southern edge of Caba, around a 15-minute tricycle ride from the town proper. The beach is short, around 200 meters of gray-brown sand, fronted by a few small cottages. The water is calm and shallow, suitable for swimming and for kids. Day-use fees are modest and the cottage rentals come with a basic bamboo table.</p>
<p>The cove is rarely crowded on weekdays. Vendors are minimal so bring your own snacks. The southern headland has a small rock outcrop that you can climb for a view of the coast.</p>
<h2>Day One Afternoon: Caba Town Center</h2>
<p>The Caba church is the Saint Therese of the Child Jesus Parish, a small stone structure with a plain facade and a wooden interior. The plaza in front is the town center and the locals gather in the late afternoon for chess and merienda. The public market is one block away and serves the local catch and produce.</p>
<p>Walk past the old municipal hall and the small heritage houses on Calle Real. A few of the houses are still occupied by the original families and the wooden balconies face the street. Plan around 30 minutes for the slow walk through the town center.</p>
<h2>Day Two: Coastal Ride and the Fishing Barangays</h2>
<p>Rent a bike or hire a tricycle for a coastal loop through Caba's barangays. The route from Liguay south to the boundary with Aringay covers around eight kilometers of small fishing villages, mangrove patches, and coastal road with views of Lingayen Gulf. Around two hours round trip with photo stops.</p>
<p>Stop at the Caba public beach near the church for a calm morning swim. The water here is calmer than Liguay and the locals are used to visitors. Bring your own towel and water.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Cubao or Pasay, take a Partas or Victory Liner bus bound for San Fernando La Union and ask to be dropped at Caba. Travel time is around five and a half hours. From San Fernando, jeepneys run south every 15 minutes during daylight hours. By car, TPLEX to Rosario, then Manila North Road north through Agoo and Aringay to Caba.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat</h2>
<p>The carinderias around the Caba plaza serve early breakfast and rice meals. Ilocos longganisa, bagnet, and pinakbet are the standard orders. For a sit-down meal, drive 20 minutes north to San Fernando city for the eateries along the National Highway.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through May is the dry window. June through October the southern La Union coast gets the southwest monsoon swells. Sundays during summer fill Liguay Cove with the local crowd, but weekday mornings rarely have more than 20 visitors.</p>
<p>Caba is the La Union town that does not appear on the surf-strip itinerary and quietly rewards the slow traveler. Walk the plaza, swim at Liguay, and the trip gives you the southern La Union without the Bauang resort row.</p>
