    // 16. SAN GABRIEL LA UNION TANGADAN FALLS EXTENDED
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.travelaroundph.com/la-union-travel-guide',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Travel Around Philippines',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'San Gabriel La Union: The Tangadan Falls Extended Trek',
        'slug' => 'san-gabriel-la-union-tangadan-falls-extended-trek',
        'excerpt' => 'San Gabriel sits inland from San Juan La Union and holds Tangadan Falls. Here is the diy plan for the extended trek to the upper tiers.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>San Gabriel is the inland mountain town of La Union, around 30 minutes east of San Juan by tricycle. Most surfers visit Tangadan Falls as a day trip from the surf strip and walk only to the lower pool, but the falls has three more tiers above the main basin that few visitors see. This is the diy extended trek for the upper falls and the surrounding ridge.</p>
<p>The trail starts at the San Gabriel registration area. Tara, here is the day by stage.</p>
<h2>Stage One: The Lower Pool</h2>
<p>The lower pool is the popular swimming spot, fed by the main 10-meter waterfall. The walk from the registration area takes around 20 minutes through farmland and one shallow river crossing. The pool is wide and deep, rimmed by jumping rocks around three meters above the water.</p>
<p>Most day-trippers stop here. The pool can hold around 30 swimmers comfortably, but weekend afternoons get crowded. Go early; the morning light hits the falls around eight to ten in the morning.</p>
<h2>Stage Two: The Second Tier</h2>
<p>A small unmarked trail starts behind the lower pool and climbs the right side of the falls for around 25 minutes. The path is steep and uses tree roots as handholds in places. A local guide from the registration area is required for the upper sections; the trail is not well-marked and the rocks get slippery after rain.</p>
<p>The second tier is a smaller falls with a shallow pool, around three meters wide. Few visitors come up here. The pool is good for a quick dip and a rest before the climb continues.</p>
<h2>Stage Three: The Upper Tiers</h2>
<p>The trail continues from the second tier through a narrower bamboo grove for another 30 minutes. The third tier is a long cascade rather than a single drop, around 20 meters of water sliding over smooth rock. The pool at the base is the deepest of the upper tiers, around two meters at the center.</p>
<p>The fourth tier is the smallest, more of a series of small pools fed by a 2-meter trickle. The total elevation gain from the registration area to the fourth tier is around 250 meters, doable in a half day if you start by eight in the morning.</p>
<h2>The Return</h2>
<p>The return follows the same trail back down. Allow around 90 minutes for the descent. The lower pool is the natural endpoint where you can swim, eat lunch from your packed food, and rest before the tricycle ride back to San Juan.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From San Juan, take a tricycle to San Gabriel proper, around 30 minutes. From the town center, another tricycle to the Lon-oy registration area, around 15 minutes. Total travel time from San Fernando city is around an hour.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<p>Trail runners or aqua shoes with grip. Quick-dry shorts and shirt. Small daypack with one to two liters of water. Snacks and a packed lunch. Insect repellent. Dry bag for valuables. A small towel. The local guide fee is around 300 to 500 pesos for the extended trek; arrange it at the registration area.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November through May is the dry window and the safest for the extended trek. The upper tiers are unsafe during the wet season from June to October; the trail is slippery and the falls are at full volume with strong undercurrents. Weekday mornings are the quietest; weekend afternoons get the day-tripper crowd at the lower pool.</p>
<p>The Tangadan extended trek is the rare La Union half-day that gets you past the surf-strip day-tripper version of the falls. Bring the right shoes, hire a guide, and the upper tiers stop feeling like a rumor.</p>
