    // 18. CARAMOAN CIRCUIT TWO-DAY ISLAND HOPPING
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.escapemanila.com/top-tourist-spots-in-camarines-norte-and-how-to-get-there/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'EscapeManila',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Caramoan Two-Day Circuit: An Honest Island Hopping Plan',
        'slug' => 'caramoan-two-day-circuit-honest-island-hopping-plan',
        'excerpt' => 'Caramoan in Camarines Sur has dozens of small islands. Here is the slow two-day circuit that covers the calmer ones beyond the Survivor sites.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Caramoan is the long peninsula in southeastern Camarines Sur, known for hosting multiple Survivor TV seasons and for the limestone island cluster off its eastern coast. Most travelers do a one-day rush through five islands; few plan a calmer two-day circuit that gives you actual swim time and a couple of overnight beaches. This is the slow plan for a two-day Caramoan trip.</p>
<p>The launch is from Paniman Beach near the town proper. Tara, here is the circuit by day.</p>
<h2>Day One: The North Cluster</h2>
<p>Launch from Paniman by eight in the morning. The first stop is Matukad Island, a small limestone outcrop with a short climb to a hidden lake that holds a single bangus, kept there by local lore. The climb takes around 15 minutes one way; sandals with grip are essential. The white-coral beach at the base is good for a short swim.</p>
<p>The second stop is Lahos Island, a sandbar fronted by two limestone walls. The water is shallow and clear, with snorkeling visibility around three meters. Plan around 90 minutes for lunch and a swim.</p>
<p>The third stop is Sabitang-Laya, the longer beach island on the northern circuit. The sand is white and powdery, the beach is around 600 meters long, and the eastern end has shade from old talisay trees. Camping is allowed; if you want the overnight option, set up here.</p>
<h2>Day One Sunset: Sabitang-Laya Overnight</h2>
<p>If you camp, the sunset across the western horizon is the calm moment of the trip. The beach faces the open South China Sea and the sky turns deep orange around five forty in the dry season. Bring your own tent, sleeping mat, food, and water. No commercial vendors. Toilet facilities are basic.</p>
<p>The boat operator stays with you or returns the next morning, depending on the deal. Most operators agree to overnight stays for an additional fee.</p>
<h2>Day Two: The South Cluster</h2>
<p>The boat picks you up by seven in the morning. The first stop is Cotivas Island, a small sandbar with white coral. Snorkeling is good along the northern reef edge. Plan around 60 minutes.</p>
<p>The second stop is Manlawi Sandbar, a long shallow bar that emerges at low tide and disappears at high. Time the visit to low tide for the full walking experience. The boat operator usually knows the schedule.</p>
<p>The final stop is Tugawe Cove or Hunongan Cove for a calm late-morning swim before the return to Paniman by mid-afternoon. The boat ride back takes around 45 minutes.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Manila, take a DLTBCo or Philtranco bus to Naga or Sabang Pier in San Jose Camarines Sur. From Sabang, the daily ferry to Guijalo Port in Caramoan runs around two and a half hours. Total travel time is around 14 hours one way. By plane, fly to Naga or Legazpi from Manila, then connect by van to Sabang.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<p>All your food and water for two days if you camp. Tent, sleeping mat, basic cooking gear. Insect repellent. Sandals with grip for the limestone climbs. Snorkel and mask. Power bank. Dry bag for valuables.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>March through May is the dry window and the calmest sea. June through October is typhoon season; boat trips often cancel. November through February is dry but the northeast monsoon can choppy the eastern coast. Weekday departures are quieter; weekend boat parties from Naga can crowd the popular islands.</p>
<p>Caramoan is the rare Philippine island cluster where two days gives you a meaningful overnight rather than a rushed five-stop checklist. Bring the right gear, find an honest boat operator, and the trip rewards the slow plan.</p>
