    // 19. BULAN SORSOGON COAST SMALL TOWN
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.escapemanila.com/2018/03/tropical-charm-of-matnog-sorsogon.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'EscapeManila',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Bulan Sorsogon: A Small Coastal Town Read',
        'slug' => 'bulan-sorsogon-small-coastal-town-read',
        'excerpt' => 'Bulan is a fishing town of Sorsogon between Matnog and Irosin. Here is the slow weekend plan for the church, the coast, and the public market.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Bulan is the largest of the southern Sorsogon coastal towns, sitting around 90 minutes south of Sorsogon City on the way to Matnog. Most travelers blow through it on the bus to the Samar ferry, but the town has a calm coast, a 17th-century stone church, and a public market that handles the regional catch from the Visayan Sea. This is a slow weekend plan for the Bulan coastal angle.</p>
<p>The town center sits along the main highway and the coast is a few blocks west. Tara, here is the weekend by day.</p>
<h2>Day One: Town Center and the Old Church</h2>
<p>The Bulan church is the Saint James the Greater Parish, originally built in 1631 and rebuilt several times after earthquakes. The current facade is plain late baroque with a single bell tower. The interior holds a wooden retablo with the image of Santiago and the side altars of the patron saints. Free entry, weekday mass at six in the morning.</p>
<p>The plaza in front is the town center and the locals gather in the late afternoon for chess and merienda. The municipal hall sits on the eastern side and the streets around it have a few surviving 19th-century houses with wide wooden balconies.</p>
<h2>Day One Afternoon: Bulan Public Market</h2>
<p>The public market is one block from the church and serves the regional catch from the Visayan Sea. Fishermen unload from late afternoon onward, around three to five in the afternoon. The catch includes tanigue, lapu-lapu, the local pusit, and the cheap kanduli. Pick up a kilo of fresh fish if you have a cooler; the price is around half of the Manila wet market rate.</p>
<p>The market also sells the local pili nut products: pili candy, pili tart, and the salted pili nut snack. Pili is the Sorsogon specialty and the Bulan vendors carry the better-quality versions.</p>
<h2>Day Two: Bulan Coast</h2>
<p>Walk four blocks west from the plaza to the Bulan coast. The shore is fronted by a long concrete promenade with benches, used by locals for early morning walks and evening jogs. The beach proper is dark sand and the water is shallow for around 20 meters out. Not a swimming beach, more of a walking and sitting coast.</p>
<p>The southern end of the promenade has a small fishing village where the bancas pull up between launches. Walk past in the late afternoon for the boat-and-net scene. Locals are friendly and used to the occasional visitor.</p>
<h2>Other Stops</h2>
<p>If you have a third half-day, drive 30 minutes inland to the Brgy Mabini hot springs in the foothills of Mount Bulusan. The springs are basic, fed by underground volcanic heat, and the soak is around 38 degrees Celsius. Bring your own swimwear and water.</p>
<p>Alternatively, drive 45 minutes south to Matnog for the Subic Beach pink-sand day trip. The boat to Subic launches from the Matnog port.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Manila, take a DLTBCo or Philtranco bus to Sorsogon City, then a smaller bus to Bulan. Total travel time is around 13 hours one way. By plane, fly to Legazpi from Manila, then a van to Sorsogon and Bulan, around three hours total from Legazpi.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat</h2>
<p>The carinderias around the Bulan plaza serve early breakfast and rice meals. Sinigang sa miso, ginataang gulay, and the local laing are the regular orders. The sili ice cream from the small carts near the market is the famous Bicol sweet-spicy combination; try one even if the heat sounds odd.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November through May is the dry window. June through October is typhoon season; the southern Sorsogon coast gets the brunt of storms. Weekday mornings are quietest at the market. Holy Week and the August town fiesta fill the plaza.</p>
<p>Bulan is the calm Sorsogon town that rewards the visitor who pauses on the bus route. Eat at the market, walk the promenade, and the trip gives you the southern Bicol without the Matnog ferry rush.</p>
