    // 20. CATANDUANES BATO TO VIRAC CIRCUIT
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.escapemanila.com/2019/03/5-budget-hotels-and-resorts-in-catanduanes.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'EscapeManila',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Catanduanes: The Bato to Virac Coastal Circuit',
        'slug' => 'catanduanes-bato-to-virac-coastal-circuit',
        'excerpt' => 'Catanduanes is the easternmost island of Bicol. Here is the slow two-day circuit from Bato to Virac covering the church, the coast, and the small towns.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Catanduanes is the easternmost island of the Bicol region, separated from the mainland by the Maqueda Channel. Most travelers go for the Puraran surf or the Binurong Point cliff, but the western coast between Bato and Virac holds a series of small heritage towns, a long stretch of coastal road, and a slower pace that gives you the calm side of the island. This is a two-day circuit for the Bato to Virac stretch.</p>
<p>The island is reached by ferry from Tabaco port in Albay. Tara, here is the circuit by day.</p>
<h2>Day One: Bato and the Stone Church</h2>
<p>The Bato church is the Saint John the Baptist Parish, built in 1830 with a stone facade that survived multiple typhoons. The bell tower is detached from the main church and the interior holds a wooden retablo with the original altarpieces. Free entry, weekday mass at six in the morning. The plaza in front is the Bato town center.</p>
<p>Walk three blocks east from the plaza to the Bato River. The river runs into the sea at a wide delta with mangroves on both banks. A small concrete walkway follows the river for around 20 minutes one way. The locals use it for evening walks.</p>
<h2>Day One Afternoon: Coastal Drive</h2>
<p>Hire a tricycle or rent a motorcycle for the coastal drive from Bato north to Virac. The road covers around 25 kilometers of small fishing villages, beach stretches, and the Caramoan Sea view. Around two hours with photo stops.</p>
<p>Stop at the Saint Andrew the Apostle Parish in Virac, the larger of the island's two old churches. The facade is plain late baroque with a single bell tower. The interior is bigger than Bato and holds a more elaborate retablo. Plan around 20 minutes for the visit.</p>
<h2>Day Two: Virac Town and the Eastern Beaches</h2>
<p>Spend the morning in Virac for the public market and the small heritage walk. The market handles the regional catch from the eastern coast and the inland produce from the central plateau. Buy a kilo of pili and the local kakanin if you have a cooler.</p>
<p>Walk the streets around the plaza for the surviving wooden houses from the early 20th century. The town hall is a stone building from the American colonial period with a working clock tower.</p>
<h2>Day Two Afternoon: Mamangal or Magnesia Beach</h2>
<p>From Virac, drive 30 minutes east to Mamangal or Magnesia Beach. These are smaller coves on the eastern side of the island, fronted by the open Pacific. The sand is gray and the waves are bigger than the western coast; swimming is safe near the shore but the locals advise against going far out.</p>
<p>Walk the beach for around 30 minutes. The view east opens to the Pacific Ocean and the next island stop is Samar across the open sea. Late afternoon light is the best window for photos.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Manila, fly to Legazpi or Naga, then a van to Tabaco port. The ferry to Virac runs around three hours twice daily. Total travel time including the flight is around six hours. By bus, total travel time is around 16 hours one way; not recommended for a short weekend.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat</h2>
<p>The carinderias around the Bato and Virac plazas serve Bicol staples: laing, Bicol Express, pinangat, and ginataang gulay. The sili sauce from Catanduanes is hotter than the mainland version; warn the kitchen if you cannot handle the heat.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through May is the dry window. June through November is typhoon season; the eastern Bicol islands get the strongest storms. Avoid Holy Week if you want the towns quiet; the local diaspora returns and the plazas fill up.</p>
<p>Catanduanes is the rare Bicol island where the heritage angle is stronger than the beach angle. Walk the Bato church, drive the coastal road, and the trip gives you the eastern edge of Luzon without the Puraran surf detour.</p>
