    // 21. ALOGUINSAN CEBU BOJO RIVER CRUISE
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.escapemanila.com/oslob-cebu-to-panglao-bohol-by-ferry/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'EscapeManila',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Aloguinsan Cebu: The Bojo River Cruise Calm Day',
        'slug' => 'aloguinsan-cebu-bojo-river-cruise-calm-day',
        'excerpt' => 'Aloguinsan sits on the western coast of Cebu. Here is the day-trip plan for the Bojo River cruise and the surrounding heritage walk.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Aloguinsan is a small coastal town of western Cebu, around two hours from Cebu City by van. It is best known for the Bojo River, a community-managed eco-tourism site where local guides paddle visitors through a mangrove tunnel that opens into the Tanon Strait. The river cruise is one of the calmest river experiences in the Visayas and the town itself holds a 19th-century church and a small heritage walk. This is a day-trip plan from Cebu City.</p>
<p>The river launch is at Brgy Bojo on the western coast. Tara, here is the day by stop.</p>
<h2>Bojo River Cruise</h2>
<p>The cruise is run by the Bojo Aloguinsan Ecotourism Association, a community organization that trains local fishermen as guides. Boats are small paddle bancas that hold four to six passengers each. The cruise lasts around 75 minutes one way and the river runs through a narrow mangrove tunnel, then opens into a small estuary and the Tanon Strait.</p>
<p>The guides know the local plant and bird species; the river hosts kingfishers, herons, and the occasional sea snake on the lower stretches. The water is clear and shallow, around two meters at the deepest. The cruise rate covers the guide and the boat rental; a community lunch with local Cebuano dishes is available as an add-on at the visitor center.</p>
<h2>The Estuary and the Tanon Strait</h2>
<p>The cruise turns around at the estuary near the Tanon Strait opening. On a clear day, you can see Negros Island across the strait. The boats stop for around 20 minutes for swimming or quiet observation before paddling back upriver. Bring water and a small snack; the cruise has no commercial stops along the way.</p>
<h2>Aloguinsan Town Center</h2>
<p>After the cruise, drive 15 minutes back to the town center for lunch. The Aloguinsan church is the Santa Cruz Parish, a 19th-century stone structure with a plain facade and a single bell tower. The plaza in front is the town center and the locals gather in the late afternoon for chess and merienda.</p>
<p>Walk the streets around the plaza for the surviving wooden houses from the early 20th century. The town hall is a small concrete building with a working clock tower. The public market sits one block south.</p>
<h2>The Hermit's Cove</h2>
<p>If you have a second half-day, drive 30 minutes south to Hermit's Cove in the boundary with Barili. The cove is a small white-sand beach fronted by limestone cliffs, accessible by a 10-minute walk down a steep path. The water is calm and clear; snorkeling visibility is around four meters. Day-use fees are modest.</p>
<p>Plan around two hours at the cove. Bring water shoes for the rocky entry into the water.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Cebu City, take a Ceres bus from the Cebu South Bus Terminal bound for Toledo or Pinamungajan, and ask to be dropped at Aloguinsan. Travel time is around two hours. From Toledo, smaller jeepneys and tricycles run south to Aloguinsan. By car, follow the transcentral highway from Cebu City over the central mountain range and down to the western coast.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat</h2>
<p>The community lunch at the Bojo visitor center is the recommended meal. The menu changes daily but typically includes grilled fish, kinilaw, ginataang gulay, and rice. The dishes are made by the local women's association as part of the community livelihood program. Order ahead if your group is more than four.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through May is the dry window. June through October the Tanon Strait gets choppy and the cruise sometimes cancels. The cruise runs from seven in the morning to four in the afternoon. Early morning slots have the best light and the calmest water. Weekday slots are quieter than weekends.</p>
<p>Aloguinsan is the rare western Cebu town where the eco-tourism setup is community-managed and the experience feels honest. Combine it with a Pinamungajan or Barili coastal stop for a slower west-Cebu day.</p>
