        'excerpt' => 'Badian is known for Kawasan Falls but the town also holds Lambug Beach. Here is the slow weekend plan for the quieter Badian coastal side.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Badian is the southwestern Cebu town where most travelers go for Kawasan Falls and the canyoneering route. The town also holds Lambug Beach, a long white-sand stretch on the western coast that the canyoneering crowd usually skips. This is the slow weekend plan for the Badian coastal side, away from the falls queue.</p>
<p>The town center sits along the highway and Lambug is a 15-minute drive south. Tara, here is the weekend by day.</p>
<h2>Day One: Lambug Beach</h2>
<p>Lambug is around one kilometer of white-sand beach fronted by the Tanon Strait. The sand is powdery, the water is shallow and clear for around 30 meters out, and the beach is rarely as crowded as Moalboal or Oslob. Day-use fees are modest and the cottage rentals come with basic amenities. A few small carinderias serve grilled fish and rice.</p>
<p>The beach faces west, so sunset is the calm moment of the day. The sun drops behind Negros Island around five forty-five in the dry season. The water turns gold and the few small bancas on the shore make for a quiet provincial scene.</p>
<h2>Day One Afternoon: Badian Town Center</h2>
<p>The Badian church is the Saint James the Greater Parish, built in 1839 with a plain stone facade. The bell tower is detached from the main church and the interior holds a wooden retablo with the image of Santiago. Free entry, weekday mass at six in the morning. The plaza in front is the town center.</p>
<p>Walk the streets around the plaza for the surviving stone houses from the late Spanish period. The streets are narrow and shaded by old acacia trees. The municipal hall sits on the eastern side.</p>
<h2>Day Two: Matutinao and the Calm Side</h2>
<p>Drive 20 minutes south to Brgy Matutinao for the second day. Matutinao is the launch barangay for Kawasan Falls but it also has a small fishing coast that is quiet during weekday mornings. The shore is dark sand and the water is deeper than Lambug; locals use the bay for boat launches and small-scale fishing.</p>
<p>If you have not done Kawasan yet, the lower pool is a 15-minute walk from Matutinao. The trail is paved and easy. Go before nine in the morning to avoid the canyoneering crowd. The pool is calm in the early morning, around 10 to 20 swimmers compared to the 200 plus on a busy afternoon.</p>
<h2>Other Stops</h2>
<p>The Badian inland barangays sit in the foothills of the Cebu central range. A 30-minute drive east takes you to small mountain communities with rice terraces and a few small streams. The road is paved and the route is suitable for a motorbike ride. Plan around two hours round trip with photo stops.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Cebu City, take a Ceres bus from the Cebu South Bus Terminal bound for Bato or Moalboal and ask to be dropped at Badian. Travel time is around three and a half hours. By car, follow the southern coastal highway through Naga, Carcar, and Argao. Total around 100 kilometers from Cebu City.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat</h2>
<p>The carinderias around the Badian plaza serve early breakfast and rice meals. Grilled tuna, kinilaw, ginataang gulay, and the local utan bisaya are the regular orders. For a sit-down meal, the eateries near Kawasan in Matutinao serve traditional Cebuano lunches.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through May is the dry window. The southern Cebu coast gets less rain than the eastern side. Weekday mornings are calmest at Lambug. Holy Week and the December break fill the town with the canyoneering crowd, but Lambug stays relatively quiet.</p>
<p>Badian is the southern Cebu town that gives you a calm beach option once the Kawasan crowd thins out. Walk the church plaza, swim at Lambug, and the weekend feels slower than the standard south Cebu rush.</p>
