    // 23. BOLJOON CEBU HERITAGE CHURCH WALK
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.escapemanila.com/oslob-cebu-to-panglao-bohol-by-ferry/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'EscapeManila',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Boljoon Cebu: A Heritage Church and Watchtower Walk',
        'slug' => 'boljoon-cebu-heritage-church-watchtower-walk',
        'excerpt' => 'Boljoon holds one of the oldest church complexes in Cebu. Here is the slow half-day walk through the heritage town and the coastal watchtower.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Boljoon is a small southern Cebu town that holds one of the oldest and most intact church complexes in the Visayas. The Patrocinio de Maria Parish was built in 1599 and the surrounding complex includes the convent, the old cemetery, and a coastal watchtower from the 18th century. Most travelers blow through Boljoon on the way to Oslob, but the heritage walk is a half-day stop worth the slow read. This is the plan for the walk.</p>
<p>The complex sits in the town center along the coastal highway. Tara, here is the walk by stop.</p>
<h2>Patrocinio de Maria Parish</h2>
<p>The church is a stone structure from the late 16th century with multiple rebuilds over the next 300 years. The facade is plain late baroque with twin bell towers and the interior holds the original wooden retablo, declared a National Cultural Treasure by the National Museum. The retablo carvings include the patron saints of the parish and the original altar from the 17th century.</p>
<p>Free entry, modest dress, weekday mass at six in the morning. A small museum to the right of the nave holds period artifacts: vestments, a 17th-century chalice, and the original baptismal records. Allot 45 minutes for the church and the museum.</p>
<h2>El Gran Baluarte Watchtower</h2>
<p>The watchtower sits across the coastal highway from the church, around a two-minute walk. It is the largest surviving Spanish-era watchtower in the Visayas, built in the 18th century to guard the coast against Moro raiders. The structure is a three-story coral-stone tower with a flat top that gave sentries a clear view of the Bohol Strait.</p>
<p>You can climb to the top for a small fee. The view east opens to the strait and on a clear day you can see Bohol across the water. The climb is short, around five minutes, and the top has a basic wooden floor and railings.</p>
<h2>Old Cemetery and Convent</h2>
<p>The old cemetery sits behind the church, marked by a stone arch entrance from the 19th century. The graves are mostly modern with a few older stone markers from the late Spanish period. Walk through the side gate for the slow heritage read; the cemetery is quiet on weekday afternoons.</p>
<p>The convent is attached to the church and serves as the parish office. The original structure dates from the 17th century, rebuilt in the 19th. The lower courtyard has a small museum-style display of old religious items and parish records.</p>
<h2>Town Center and the Coast</h2>
<p>Walk the streets around the plaza for the surviving wooden houses from the early 20th century. The Boljoon coast sits behind the church complex and holds a small concrete promenade with benches. The locals use it for evening walks. The water is calm and the view east is the Bohol Strait.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Cebu City, take a Ceres bus from the Cebu South Bus Terminal bound for Bato or Oslob and ask to be dropped at Boljoon. Travel time is around three and a half hours. By car, follow the southern coastal highway through Naga, Carcar, Argao, and Dalaguete. Total around 110 kilometers.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat</h2>
<p>The carinderias around the Boljoon plaza serve early breakfast and rice meals. Sinigang sa lemoncito, ginataang gulay, and the local utan bisaya are the regular orders. For a sit-down meal, drive 30 minutes south to Oslob for the eateries near the whale shark interaction area.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through May is the dry window. The church complex is open year-round. Weekday mornings are quietest; Sunday mornings fill the church for the parish mass. The Patrocinio de Maria feast day on the third Sunday of November fills the plaza with the local fiesta crowd.</p>
<p>Boljoon is the southern Cebu town where the heritage angle is stronger than the beach. Walk the church, climb the watchtower, and the half-day stop becomes the calmer alternative to the Oslob whale shark rush.</p>
