    // 24. ARGAO CEBU COLONIAL STOP
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.escapemanila.com/oslob-cebu-to-panglao-bohol-by-ferry/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'EscapeManila',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Argao Cebu: A Colonial Stop and the Torta Trail',
        'slug' => 'argao-cebu-colonial-stop-torta-trail',
        'excerpt' => 'Argao is a heritage town on the southern Cebu coast. Here is the slow day plan for the church complex, the old houses, and the famous torta.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Argao is a heritage town on the southern Cebu coast, around two hours from Cebu City. It is one of the older Spanish settlements on the island, founded in 1608, and the town center holds the Saint Michael the Archangel Parish, a colonial complex with a fortified wall, a watchtower, and a series of bahay-na-bato houses around the plaza. Argao is also the home of the Cebu torta, a local sponge cake made with tuba lambanog and lard. This is a slow day plan for the heritage walk and the torta trail.</p>
<p>The complex sits in the town center along the highway. Tara, here is the day by stop.</p>
<h2>Saint Michael the Archangel Parish</h2>
<p>The church was built in 1734 and the surrounding complex includes the convent, a fortified wall, and a watchtower. The facade is late baroque with a single bell tower and the interior holds a wooden retablo with the image of Saint Michael. The retablo and the side altars are among the more elaborate in the Visayas. Free entry, weekday mass at six in the morning.</p>
<p>The convent is attached to the church and serves as the parish office. The original structure dates from the 18th century with later expansions. The lower courtyard has a small museum-style display of old religious items and parish records.</p>
<h2>The Fortified Wall and Watchtower</h2>
<p>The Argao complex is one of the few in the Visayas that retained its fortified perimeter wall. The wall is coral stone, around four meters tall, and runs around the church and the convent. The original purpose was defense against Moro raiders during the 18th century. Walk along the wall for around 15 minutes for the full perimeter loop.</p>
<p>The watchtower sits on the southwest corner of the wall, a three-story stone structure that gave sentries a view of the coast. You can climb to the top for a small fee and a view of the southern Cebu coast.</p>
<h2>Plaza and the Bahay-na-Bato Walk</h2>
<p>The plaza in front of the church is the town center and holds a small gazebo and the municipal hall. The streets around the plaza have a series of bahay-na-bato houses from the late 19th century, some still occupied by the original families. The Casa Real, a stone-and-wood house from 1850, is one of the better preserved. Most are private residences and not open to visitors, but you can walk past them on a 30-minute heritage loop.</p>
<h2>The Torta Trail</h2>
<p>Argao is the home of the Cebu torta, a sponge cake made with tuba lambanog and lard. Several bakeries around the town center sell the local version; the most well-known is the Lola Inday torta, available at small stalls near the public market. The torta is dense, slightly sweet, and best eaten with hot chocolate or strong coffee.</p>
<p>Walk the bakery trail for around 30 minutes, sampling slices from three to four vendors. Each baker has a slightly different recipe; the older versions use more lard and have a denser crumb. Buy a whole torta to bring home if you have a cooler; the cake keeps for around five days at room temperature.</p>
<h2>Argao Beachfront</h2>
<p>The Argao coast sits behind the church complex, around a five-minute walk. The shore is dark sand and the water is shallow. Not a swimming beach, more of a sitting and walking coast. The locals use the small concrete promenade for evening walks.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Cebu City, take a Ceres bus from the Cebu South Bus Terminal bound for Bato or Oslob and ask to be dropped at Argao. Travel time is around two and a half hours. By car, follow the southern coastal highway through Naga and Carcar. Total around 70 kilometers.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through May is the dry window. The Saint Michael the Archangel feast day on September 29 is the headline town fiesta. Weekday mornings are calmest. The bakeries sell torta year-round; the freshest batches come out by mid-morning.</p>
<p>Argao is the heritage stop on the southern Cebu run that rewards the slow visitor. Walk the church, taste the torta, and the day becomes more than a drive-through on the way to Boljoon or Oslob.</p>
