    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 25. ANDA BOHOL QUINALE BEACH
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.escapemanila.com/top-tourist-spots-in-bohol/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'EscapeManila',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Anda Bohol: Quinale Beach and the Slow Eastern Side',
        'slug' => 'anda-bohol-quinale-beach-slow-eastern-side',
        'excerpt' => 'Anda is the calm eastern Bohol town with Quinale Beach. Here is the slow weekend plan for the white sand, cave pool, and the small inland barangays.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Anda sits on the eastern coast of Bohol, around three hours from Tagbilaran by van. It is the calmer side of the island, away from the Panglao resort row and the Loboc cruise crowd. The town holds Quinale Beach, one of the longest public white-sand beaches in the Visayas, a series of small inland cave pools, and a coastal road that gives you the slow Bohol angle. This is the weekend plan for the eastern side.</p>
<p>The town center sits along the coastal road and Quinale Beach is a five-minute walk from the plaza. Tara, here is the weekend by day.</p>
<h2>Day One: Quinale Beach</h2>
<p>Quinale is around one and a half kilometers of white-sand public beach in the heart of Anda town. The sand is powdery, the water is shallow and clear for around 40 meters out, and there is no entrance fee for the public stretch. A few cottages near the southern end charge a small day-use fee for shaded sitting. The beach has basic toilet facilities at the public side.</p>
<p>The beach faces east, so sunrise is the calm moment of the day. The sun rises over the open sea around five forty-five and the sky turns deep orange. Walk the full length of the beach for around 30 minutes one way. The northern end has a small headland with a view of the coast.</p>
<h2>Day One Afternoon: Anda Town Center</h2>
<p>The Anda church is the Santo Nino Parish, a small concrete structure rebuilt in the 20th century after the original stone church was damaged. The plaza in front is the town center and the locals gather in the late afternoon for chess and merienda. The public market is one block east.</p>
<p>Walk the streets around the plaza for the slow town read. The municipal hall sits on the western side and the streets around it have a few small commercial buildings from the early 20th century.</p>
<h2>Day Two: Cabagnow Cave Pool</h2>
<p>Drive 10 minutes south to Cabagnow Cave Pool. The pool is a natural sinkhole filled with clear freshwater, around five meters deep at the center, accessible by a wooden ladder from the rim. Day-use fees are modest. The water is cool and refreshing after the morning beach time.</p>
<p>The pool can hold around 20 swimmers comfortably; weekend mornings get more crowded. Bring a small towel and water. The walk down to the pool is short, around five minutes from the parking area.</p>
<h2>Day Two Afternoon: Lamanok Island</h2>
<p>If you have a third half-day, drive 15 minutes north to the Lamanok Island launch. The island sits in a small bay and holds a series of caves with ancient burial sites and rock paintings. A short banca ride from the mainland takes around 10 minutes one way. The island has a small fee and a local guide is required.</p>
<p>The guide walks you through the caves and explains the local history. Plan around two hours total. Bring water and a small snack; no commercial vendors on the island.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Tagbilaran City, take a van from the Dao Integrated Terminal bound for Guindulman or Anda. Travel time is around three hours. By car, follow the eastern coastal road through Loay, Garcia Hernandez, and Jagna. Total around 110 kilometers.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat</h2>
<p>The carinderias around the Anda plaza serve early breakfast and rice meals. Sinigang na bangus, ginataang gulay, and the local kinilaw are the regular orders. For a sit-down meal, the eateries along Quinale Beach serve grilled fish and rice for late lunch.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through May is the dry window. The eastern Bohol coast gets less rain than the western side. Weekday mornings are calmest at Quinale and Cabagnow. Holy Week fills the public beach with the local crowd.</p>
<p>Anda is the eastern Bohol town that absorbs slow travelers without losing its small-town pace. Walk Quinale, swim at Cabagnow, and the weekend feels like a real Bohol countryside read.</p>
