    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 26. LOON BOHOL CHURCH AND DOLPHIN COAST
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.escapemanila.com/top-tourist-spots-in-bohol/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'EscapeManila',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Loon Bohol: The Reconstructed Church and Dolphin Watch Coast',
        'slug' => 'loon-bohol-reconstructed-church-dolphin-watch-coast',
        'excerpt' => 'Loon was the largest church in Bohol before the 2013 earthquake. Here is the slow weekend plan for the rebuild and the Pamilacan dolphin coast.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Loon is a coastal town of western Bohol, around 45 minutes from Tagbilaran by van. Before the 2013 earthquake, the Loon church was the largest in the province, a colonial stone basilica that dominated the town plaza. The earthquake leveled the church and the rebuild was completed in 2022. Loon is also the launch point for the Pamilacan Island dolphin watch. This is a slow weekend plan for the rebuilt church and the western Bohol coast.</p>
<p>The town center sits along the coastal road. Tara, here is the weekend by day.</p>
<h2>Day One: The Reconstructed Church</h2>
<p>The Our Lady of Light Parish was rebuilt from 2014 to 2022 using a mix of the original coral-stone blocks and new construction. The facade replicates the original 1855 design, and the interior holds the salvaged retablo pieces alongside new altars. The reconstruction is one of the larger heritage projects in the Visayas in the past decade. Free entry, modest dress, weekday mass at six in the morning.</p>
<p>A small exhibit on the side wall documents the earthquake damage, the salvage process, and the rebuild timeline with photographs from 2013 to 2022. Around 20 minutes is enough.</p>
<h2>Day One Afternoon: Town Plaza</h2>
<p>The plaza in front of the church is the town center and the locals gather in the late afternoon for chess and merienda. The municipal hall sits on the eastern side and the streets around it have a few small commercial buildings and the public market.</p>
<p>Walk the streets around the plaza for the slow town read. The houses near the church include a few surviving stone-and-wood structures from the late Spanish period. Most are private residences.</p>
<h2>Day Two: Pamilacan Island Dolphin Watch</h2>
<p>The Pamilacan Island Dolphin and Whale Watching Tour launches from Loon early in the morning, around six. The community-managed tour follows the spinner dolphin and pilot whale populations in the Bohol Sea. The boat ride takes around 90 minutes one way to the sighting grounds.</p>
<p>Dolphin sightings are nearly daily; whale sightings are less common but happen a few times a month from March to June. The tour is run by the Pamilacan Island Dolphin and Whale Watching Organization, a community group of former hunters who now guide the watch trips. The fee covers the boat, the guide, and a community lunch on the island after the watch.</p>
<h2>Day Two Afternoon: Pamilacan Island</h2>
<p>After the watch, the boat docks at Pamilacan for lunch and a short island walk. The island has a small white-sand beach on the southern side and a small chapel in the village center. Plan around three hours for lunch, the beach, and the walk before the return boat to Loon.</p>
<p>The community lunch typically includes grilled fish, kinilaw, ginataang gulay, and rice. The dishes are made by the women's association as part of the community livelihood program.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Tagbilaran City, take a van from the Dao Integrated Terminal bound for Tubigon or Loon. Travel time is around 45 minutes. From Cebu City, take the ferry to Tagbilaran from Pier 1, then a van to Loon. Tubigon Port is closer to Loon if you take the ferry to Tubigon instead.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat</h2>
<p>The carinderias around the Loon plaza serve early breakfast and rice meals. Sinigang na bangus, ginataang gulay, and the local kinilaw are the regular orders. For a sit-down meal, the eateries along the coastal road serve grilled fish for late lunch.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through May is the dry window. The dolphin watch runs year-round but the calmer dry months have better sea conditions. Weekday mornings are calmest at the church. The Our Lady of Light feast day on October 7 is the headline town fiesta.</p>
<p>Loon is the western Bohol town where the heritage rebuild and the dolphin watch combine into a calm weekend. Skip the Panglao resort row and the trip becomes a different read of the island.</p>
