    // 27. LOBOC BOHOL OFF-CRUISE QUIET MORNING
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.escapemanila.com/top-tourist-spots-in-bohol/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'EscapeManila',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Loboc Bohol: An Off-Cruise Quiet Morning in Town',
        'slug' => 'loboc-bohol-off-cruise-quiet-morning-town',
        'excerpt' => 'Loboc is known for the river cruise, but the town itself has a slow morning angle. Here is the diy plan for the church, the river walk, and the Loboc Childrens Choir story.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Loboc is the riverside town of central Bohol, around 30 minutes from Tagbilaran. Most tourists do the floating restaurant cruise on the Loboc River and leave. The town itself, though, has a slow morning angle that the cruise crowd skips: a colonial stone church, a quiet river walk, and the home base of the Loboc Children Choir. This is the diy plan for the off-cruise Loboc.</p>
<p>The town center sits along the river. Tara, here is the morning by stop.</p>
<h2>San Pedro Apostol Parish</h2>
<p>The Loboc church was first built in 1638 and rebuilt several times. The 2013 earthquake damaged the main nave and the bell tower; the reconstruction was completed in 2022. The facade is late baroque with a single bell tower and the interior holds the salvaged retablo with the image of Saint Peter. Free entry, weekday mass at six in the morning.</p>
<p>A small exhibit on the right side of the nave documents the earthquake damage and the rebuild. The original convent attached to the church is one of the older surviving structures, dating to the 17th century, and now serves as the parish office and a small museum.</p>
<h2>The Old Stone Bridge</h2>
<p>The old stone bridge across the Loboc River is a half-built Spanish-era structure that was never completed because it would have required demolishing part of the church. The unfinished arch sits to the east of the modern bridge as a kind of monument to colonial bureaucracy. Walk past it for the photo and the small heritage marker explains the story.</p>
<h2>Loboc Riverbank Walk</h2>
<p>The river walk follows the southern bank of the Loboc River from the bridge to the church complex, around 15 minutes one way. The path is shaded by old acacia trees and runs alongside the water. Early morning is the best window; the cruise boats start at nine and the bank gets noisier after.</p>
<p>The river is wide and calm here, with fishing bancas docked at small landings. A few small bamboo seating areas along the bank are good for a 20-minute sit with a coffee from one of the carinderias near the church.</p>
<h2>Loboc Children Choir Story</h2>
<p>The Loboc Children Choir is one of the more famous Philippine choirs internationally, founded in 1980 and trained at the Loboc Central Elementary School near the plaza. The choir has performed in over 20 countries and won several international awards. If you arrive on a weekday morning, you can sometimes hear them practicing at the school auditorium.</p>
<p>The school is not a tourist site but the small barangay hall across the street has a display of choir photographs and awards. Around 15 minutes is enough.</p>
<h2>Loboc Public Market</h2>
<p>The public market sits two blocks east of the church and handles the regional produce from the inland barangays. Vendors come down from the foothills with mountain bananas, root crops, and the local sikwate (hot chocolate). Buy a kilo of fresh budbud (sticky rice cake) from the vendors for merienda.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Tagbilaran City, take a van from the Dao Integrated Terminal bound for Sevilla or Carmen. Travel time is around 30 minutes. By car, follow the central highway from Tagbilaran east through Loay and into Loboc.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat</h2>
<p>The carinderias near the Loboc church serve early breakfast and rice meals. Sinigang na bangus, ginataang gulay, and the local kinilaw are the regular orders. For sikwate and budbud merienda, the vendors near the public market open by six in the morning.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>Year-round works for the morning walk. The river cruise runs from late morning to early afternoon. Weekday mornings before nine are the quietest; the cruise crowd arrives by ten. The Saint Peter feast day on June 29 is the headline town fiesta.</p>
<p>Loboc has a calmer side than the river cruise package implies. Walk the church, sit by the river, and the off-cruise morning becomes a different read of the most-visited Bohol town.</p>
