    // 28. SEVILLA BOHOL BAMBOO HANGING BRIDGE
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.escapemanila.com/top-tourist-spots-in-bohol/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'EscapeManila',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Sevilla Bohol: The Bamboo Hanging Bridge Half-Day',
        'slug' => 'sevilla-bohol-bamboo-hanging-bridge-half-day',
        'excerpt' => 'Sevilla is the inland Bohol town with the Sipatan Bamboo Hanging Bridge. Here is the slow half-day plan from Loboc or Tagbilaran.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Sevilla is a small inland town of Bohol, around 15 minutes east of Loboc on the way to Carmen and the Chocolate Hills. The town's main draw is the Sipatan Twin Hanging Bridge, a pair of bamboo footbridges across the Sipatan River that swing slightly as you walk over them. The bridges are short, around 40 meters each, and the crossing is one of the calmer countryside stops in central Bohol. This is the half-day plan for the bridge and the town center.</p>
<p>The bridge sits at Brgy Sipatan, a five-minute drive from the town proper. Tara, here is the half-day by stop.</p>
<h2>Sipatan Twin Hanging Bridge</h2>
<p>The two bridges are made of bamboo decking on steel cables, originally built as community footbridges to connect the two barangays across the river. The first bridge takes you from the parking side to a small island in the middle of the river. The second bridge continues from the island to the opposite bank. Together they form a loop with the river path on either side.</p>
<p>Entry fees are modest. The bridges sway noticeably as you walk; the locals are used to it but first-timers feel the motion. The crossing takes around 5 minutes each way. The river below is shallow and clear, with smooth rocks and small reef fish in the slow pools.</p>
<h2>The Riverbank Walk</h2>
<p>After the bridge, walk the small riverbank trail on the southern bank for around 20 minutes. The trail is shaded by old bamboo groves and offers small views of the river through the trees. Birds are common; the local farmers report sightings of kingfishers and small herons.</p>
<p>The trail ends at a small clearing with a view of the river. Bring water and a small snack; no commercial vendors on the trail. Plan around 90 minutes total for the bridge and the walk.</p>
<h2>Sevilla Town Center</h2>
<p>Drive five minutes back to the town center. The Sevilla church is the San Isidro Labrador Parish, a small concrete structure rebuilt in the 20th century. The plaza is small and the public market sits across the highway. The carinderias around the market serve early breakfast and rice meals all day.</p>
<p>Walk the streets around the plaza for the slow town read. The municipal hall is a small concrete building and the streets are quiet on weekday afternoons.</p>
<h2>Inland Detour: Loboc Eco Adventure Park</h2>
<p>If you have a longer half-day, drive 15 minutes south to the Loboc Eco Adventure Park for the zip line across the river canyon. The zip line is around 500 meters long and crosses the Loboc River, offering a different angle of the surrounding countryside. Entry fees are moderate.</p>
<p>Plan around two hours for the zip line and a short walk through the park. Combine it with the Sevilla bridge for a slower countryside half-day.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Tagbilaran City, take a van bound for Sevilla, Carmen, or the Chocolate Hills. Travel time is around 45 minutes. From Loboc, jeepneys and tricycles run east to Sevilla every 30 minutes. By car, follow the central highway from Tagbilaran east through Loay and Loboc.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat</h2>
<p>The carinderias around the Sevilla plaza serve early breakfast and rice meals. Sinigang na bangus, ginataang gulay, and the local kinilaw are the regular orders. For sikwate and budbud merienda, the vendors near the public market open by six in the morning.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through May is the dry window. The bamboo bridge runs year-round; the swing is more noticeable in the windy months from December to February. Weekday mornings are quietest; weekend afternoons fill with the Bohol countryside tour crowd.</p>
<p>Sevilla is the inland Bohol stop that gives you a small offbeat experience between Loboc and the Chocolate Hills. Walk the bridge, sit by the river, and the half-day becomes the slow midpoint of a countryside loop.</p>
