    // 29. SAN JOAQUIN ILOILO CUARTEL CHURCH ROUTE
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.escapemanila.com/2019/12/must-visit-places-in-the-philippines.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'EscapeManila',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'San Joaquin Iloilo: The Cuartel and Church Heritage Route',
        'slug' => 'san-joaquin-iloilo-cuartel-church-heritage-route',
        'excerpt' => 'San Joaquin sits at the southern tip of Iloilo. Here is the slow half-day plan for the colonial church, the Spanish garrison ruins, and Punta Cana.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>San Joaquin is the southernmost town of Iloilo, around two hours from Iloilo City on the coastal road. It is one of the older Spanish settlements in the province, founded in 1771, and the town holds two notable heritage sites: the San Joaquin Parish Church, a militarized colonial church with a battle scene carved on the facade, and the ruins of the Cuartel de Santo Tomas, a Spanish military garrison from the 19th century. This is the half-day plan for the heritage route.</p>
<p>The town center sits along the coastal road. Tara, here is the half-day by stop.</p>
<h2>San Joaquin Parish Church</h2>
<p>The church was built in 1869 and is one of the most unusual colonial churches in the Philippines. The facade features a high-relief carving of the Battle of Tetuan (1860), depicting the Spanish victory over Moroccan forces. The carving covers most of the upper facade and shows soldiers, horses, and the Spanish flag in a battle scene. It is the only Philippine church facade with a complete military battle scene of this scale.</p>
<p>The interior holds a wooden retablo and the side altars. The bell tower is detached and sits to the right of the main nave. Free entry, modest dress, weekday mass at six in the morning.</p>
<h2>Cuartel de Santo Tomas</h2>
<p>The cuartel ruins sit around 15 minutes inland from the church, at Brgy Carrhill. The structure was built in the 19th century as a Spanish military garrison and was used as barracks for soldiers stationed in the area. The ruins consist of a perimeter wall and a few stone foundations, partially overgrown by vegetation.</p>
<p>Entry is free. Walk through the ruins for around 20 minutes; the site has minimal signage so bring a guide if you want the historical context. Local tricycle drivers know the route and can drop you off at the entrance.</p>
<h2>The Campo Santo</h2>
<p>The old cemetery of San Joaquin sits on a small hill above the town, around 10 minutes by tricycle from the plaza. The campo santo is a circular stone structure with niches for the dead, built in the late 19th century. The view from the top opens to the southern Iloilo coast and the Panay Gulf. Free entry, modest dress.</p>
<p>Walk through the cemetery for around 15 minutes. The older niches have stone markers from the early 20th century.</p>
<h2>Punta Cana and the Coast</h2>
<p>The San Joaquin coast holds a few small beaches and a coastal road that runs south to the boundary with Antique. Punta Cana is a small white-sand beach around 20 minutes south of the town center. The water is calm and the beach is rarely crowded on weekdays. Day-use fees are modest.</p>
<p>Plan around 90 minutes at the beach for a short swim and a walk. Combine it with the heritage route for a full half-day.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Iloilo City, take a Ceres bus from the Mohon Terminal bound for San Jose Antique and ask to be dropped at San Joaquin. Travel time is around two hours. By car, follow the southern coastal road through Oton, Miag-ao, and Guimbal. Total around 70 kilometers.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat</h2>
<p>The carinderias around the San Joaquin plaza serve early breakfast and rice meals. KBL (kadyos-baboy-langka) and the local linaw-linaw are the regional orders. For a sit-down meal, drive 20 minutes north to Miag-ao for the eateries near the church.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through May is the dry window. The Battle of Tetuan feast on the third Sunday of January is the headline town fiesta. Weekday mornings are calmest at the church and the cuartel. Holy Week fills the plaza with the local crowd.</p>
<p>San Joaquin is the southern Iloilo town where the colonial heritage is more dramatic than the standard church facade. Walk the Tetuan scene, climb the campo santo, and the trip gives you a different read of the Iloilo heritage circuit.</p>
