    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 30. MIAG-AO CHURCH ILOILO HERITAGE HALF-DAY
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.escapemanila.com/2019/12/must-visit-places-in-the-philippines.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'EscapeManila',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Miag-ao Iloilo: The Fortress Church Heritage Half-Day',
        'slug' => 'miagao-iloilo-fortress-church-heritage-half-day',
        'excerpt' => 'Miag-ao Church is a UNESCO World Heritage site. Here is the slow half-day plan for the fortress church, the town walk, and the public market.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Miag-ao is a small town on the southern coast of Iloilo, around 90 minutes from Iloilo City. The town's centerpiece is the Santo Tomas de Villanueva Church, a fortress-style colonial church built in 1786 and declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1993 as part of the Baroque Churches of the Philippines. The facade is one of the most recognized in Philippine heritage architecture, featuring a stylized coconut tree carving that depicts Saint Christopher as a local figure. This is the half-day plan for the church and the town.</p>
<p>The church sits at the town center along the coastal road. Tara, here is the half-day by stop.</p>
<h2>Santo Tomas de Villanueva Church</h2>
<p>The church was built between 1787 and 1797 as a fortified structure to defend against Moro raiders. The walls are around one and a half meters thick and the church doubles as a fortress, with the two flanking bell towers serving as watchtowers. The yellow-ochre stone gives the facade its distinctive color.</p>
<p>The facade carving is the iconic feature. Saint Christopher carries the Christ Child across a stylized coconut tree, with native flora and fauna integrated into the design. The carving is a unique fusion of European Catholic iconography with local Visayan motifs. Free entry, modest dress, weekday mass at six in the morning.</p>
<h2>Church Interior and Side Wing</h2>
<p>The interior holds a wooden retablo with the original 18th-century altarpieces, restored after the World War II damage. The side wing has a small museum-style display on the church's history and the UNESCO designation. Allot 30 minutes for the church and the museum.</p>
<p>The bell tower on the left is open for climbing on weekdays. The climb is around four stories of wooden stairs and the top gives you a view of the Miag-ao plaza and the coast.</p>
<h2>Miag-ao Town Plaza</h2>
<p>The plaza in front of the church is the town center. The municipal hall sits on the eastern side and the streets around it have a few surviving stone-and-wood houses from the late Spanish period. Walk the plaza for around 20 minutes for the slow heritage read.</p>
<p>The University of the Philippines Visayas campus sits around five minutes inland from the plaza. The campus is open to visitors and has a small marine science museum. If you have an extra hour, walk the grounds.</p>
<h2>Public Market and the Local Hablon</h2>
<p>The public market sits two blocks east of the church and serves the regional catch and produce. Vendors also sell the local hablon, a traditional handwoven cloth from the Miag-ao weavers. The hablon is made on wooden floor looms and the patterns include stripes, plaids, and the traditional patadyong checkered design.</p>
<p>If you want to buy hablon directly from the weavers, ask the market vendors for directions to the weaving centers in Brgy Sologon. The weavers welcome visitors and the cloth is sold by the yard. Plan around 30 minutes at the market and weaving stop.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Iloilo City, take a Ceres bus from the Mohon Terminal bound for San Jose Antique and ask to be dropped at Miag-ao. Travel time is around 90 minutes. By car, follow the southern coastal road through Oton and Guimbal. Total around 40 kilometers.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat</h2>
<p>The carinderias around the Miag-ao plaza serve early breakfast and rice meals. KBL (kadyos-baboy-langka) and the local linaw-linaw are the regional orders. For a sit-down meal, the eateries near the public market serve traditional Ilonggo lunches.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through May is the dry window. The Salakayan Festival in February is the headline town fiesta, featuring street dancing and reenactments of the historic Moro raid defense. Weekday mornings are quietest at the church.</p>
<p>Miag-ao is the southern Iloilo town where the UNESCO heritage stands at the center of the town's daily life. Walk the church, climb the tower, and the half-day becomes the calmer way to read the Iloilo heritage circuit.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Miag-ao Iloilo: The Fortress Church Heritage Half-Day | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A half-day Miag-ao Iloilo plan covering the UNESCO fortress church, the coconut tree facade, the bell tower climb, and the hablon weaving market.',
        'tags' => 'Iloilo, Miag-ao, UNESCO, Heritage, Church',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'iloilo-city',
