    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 31. GUIMARAS CIRCUITS BEYOND MANGO FARM
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.escapemanila.com/2019/12/must-visit-places-in-the-philippines.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'EscapeManila',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Guimaras Circuits: Slow Stops Beyond the Mango Farm',
        'slug' => 'guimaras-circuits-slow-stops-beyond-mango-farm',
        'excerpt' => 'Guimaras has more than the mango plantation. Here is the slow two-day circuit covering the Trappist monastery, lighthouse, and the small coves.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Guimaras is the small island province across the strait from Iloilo City, around 15 minutes by ferry from the Ortiz wharf. Most day-trippers do the mango farm and the Alubihod beach and leave by mid-afternoon. The island has more than that, though, including a Trappist monastery, an old lighthouse, and a series of small coves on the eastern coast that few tourists visit. This is the slow two-day circuit for the calmer Guimaras angle.</p>
<p>The ferry lands at Jordan port. Tara, here is the circuit by day.</p>
<h2>Day One: Trappist Monastery and the Old Lighthouse</h2>
<p>Take a tricycle from Jordan port to the Trappist Monastery in Brgy San Miguel, around 20 minutes inland. The monastery is the only Trappist community in the Philippines, founded in 1972. The chapel is open to visitors for the daily prayer hours; the gift shop sells the local mango-based products including jam, candy, and the famous mango chutney made by the monks. Free entry, modest dress.</p>
<p>Continue to the Roca Encantada heritage house on the way back to the coast, around 30 minutes from the monastery. The house is a 1910 American colonial structure that overlooks the Guimaras Strait. Free entry from the road; the interior is private.</p>
<p>End the day at the old Guisi Lighthouse on the southern coast. The lighthouse was built in 1894 by the Spanish administration and the original tower stands in partial ruins next to the modern operating tower. The view from the rocky shore is one of the calmer sunset spots in the island.</p>
<h2>Day Two: Mango Farm and Alubihod Beach</h2>
<p>The standard tourist circuit covers the National Mango Research and Development Center, also known as the mango farm, around 30 minutes from Jordan. The center has a small visitor area with information on the local mango cultivars. The actual orchards are working agricultural land and not always open to the public. Plan around 45 minutes.</p>
<p>End at Alubihod Beach for a swim. The beach is the most-visited cove in Guimaras, around one kilometer of white-sand fronted by small bamboo cottages. Day-use fees are modest. The water is calm and clear, suitable for swimming and snorkeling. Plan around three hours for lunch and a swim.</p>
<h2>Optional Add-on: Island Hopping</h2>
<p>From Alubihod, you can negotiate a banca for an island-hopping circuit covering Turtle Island, Tatlong Pulo, and the SEAFDEC outpost. The circuit takes around three hours and covers small white-sand sandbars and snorkeling stops. The fee is per boat, split among the group.</p>
<h2>Eastern Coves and the Quiet Side</h2>
<p>If you have a third half-day, take a tricycle east to the boundary with Buenavista. The eastern coves are smaller and rarely visited by day-trippers. Bring your own snacks; vendors are minimal. Walk the coast for around 30 minutes for the slow morning read.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Iloilo City, take the ferry from Ortiz wharf to Jordan port in Guimaras. Ferries run every 15 minutes during daylight hours. From Manila, fly to Iloilo and take a taxi to Ortiz. Total travel time from Manila is around three hours.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat</h2>
<p>The carinderias near Jordan port serve early breakfast and rice meals. The local KBL (kadyos-baboy-langka) and the chicken inasal are the regional orders. Mango sweets are available at every stop; the Trappist gift shop has the higher-quality versions.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through May is the dry window. The mango harvest runs from April to June; the orchards are most active during these months. The Manggahan Festival in May is the headline event. Weekday mornings are quietest.</p>
<p>Guimaras has a slower side that the standard mango farm tour skips. Walk the monastery, climb the lighthouse, and the trip gives you the small-island feel that Iloilo day-trippers usually miss.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Guimaras Circuits: Slow Stops Beyond the Mango Farm | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A two-day Guimaras circuit covering the Trappist monastery, Guisi Lighthouse, Roca Encantada, the mango farm, Alubihod Beach, and the eastern coves.',
        'tags' => 'Guimaras, Iloilo, Island Trip, Heritage, Slow Travel',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'guimaras',
