    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 32. SOLO TRAVEL NORTHERN PHILIPPINES
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.travelaroundph.com/solo-travel-philippines',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Travel Around Philippines',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Solo Travel Northern Philippines: A Slow Two-Week Read',
        'slug' => 'solo-travel-northern-philippines-slow-two-week-read',
        'excerpt' => 'A two-week solo plan through northern Luzon, covering La Union, Sagada, Banaue, and Vigan. Practical notes on safety, transit, and pace.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Solo travel in the northern Philippines works best at a slow pace. The Cordillera and the Ilocos coast are friendly to solo travelers, the transit is reliable, and the small-town accommodations are easier to navigate alone than in the larger Visayan resort areas. This is a two-week plan covering La Union, Sagada, Banaue, and Vigan, with notes on safety and pace.</p>
<p>The route runs from San Juan La Union north and east through the Cordillera then back through the Ilocos coast. Tara, here is the plan by week.</p>
<h2>Week One: La Union to Sagada</h2>
<p>Days one to three in San Juan La Union for the surf strip. Stay at a hostel along the Urbiztondo beach for the easy social setup. Solo travelers blend into the surf crowd by the second day. Two surf lessons and a half-day to Tangadan Falls in San Gabriel cover the local angles.</p>
<p>Days four and five travel east to Baguio via Bauang, then up to Sagada via Halsema Highway. The Sagada-bound vans leave from the Dangwa Terminal in Baguio. Travel time is around six hours one way. Stay in Sagada for two nights at a guesthouse near the church. The cool weather and the small town pace are calming after the surf strip.</p>
<p>Days six and seven in Sagada cover the Echo Valley hanging coffins, the Sumaguing Cave, and the small cafe scene. Solo travelers find Sagada one of the safer Cordillera towns; the local guides are professional and the trail network is well-marked.</p>
<h2>Week Two: Banaue to Vigan</h2>
<p>Day eight travel from Sagada to Banaue. The route through Bontoc and the long descent takes around five hours. Stay in Banaue for two nights at a guesthouse with a view of the rice terraces. The Batad walk is the headline activity on day nine, around four hours round trip from the saddle.</p>
<p>Day ten descend back to Baguio or directly to Vigan via the long bus route. The Vigan-bound bus from Baguio takes around eight hours; an overnight stop in San Fernando La Union breaks the journey.</p>
<p>Days 11 to 13 in Vigan for the heritage walk. Stay at a guesthouse on Calle Crisologo or the side streets. The town is walkable and the calesa rides cover the longer stretches. Solo travelers find Vigan friendly; the local culture is open to visitors and the food scene is one of the better in the north.</p>
<p>Day 14 travel back to Manila via the overnight bus or fly from Laoag if the budget allows.</p>
<h2>Safety Notes</h2>
<p>Northern Luzon is among the safer regions for solo travel in the Philippines. The Cordillera is conservative and small-town; petty theft is rare and the locals are protective of visitors. The Ilocos coast is more developed but still calm. Common-sense precautions apply: keep documents in a money belt, avoid late-night solo walks in unfamiliar areas, and check transport schedules in advance.</p>
<p>For solo women travelers, the same notes apply. The Cordillera and the Ilocos provinces have lower harassment rates than the urban centers. Dressing modestly in the smaller towns reduces unwanted attention but is not strictly required.</p>
<h2>Transit Tips</h2>
<p>Bus reservations are not always required for solo travelers; the smaller companies allow walk-on passengers. For the Cordillera routes, book the morning departures; the afternoon vans can be cramped. The Manila Bus to La Union and Vigan runs from Cubao and Pasay terminals every hour.</p>
<h2>Pace and Budget</h2>
<p>The two-week pace gives you breathing room. Plan one travel day for every two activity days. Solo travel budgets run lower than couple budgets due to dorm accommodations and shared meals. A two-week trip on a moderate budget covers transit, food, lodging, and activity fees comfortably.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through February is the cool dry window and the best for the Cordillera. April through May is the surf season in La Union. Avoid Holy Week if you want quiet roads and small towns. The June to October wet season makes the Cordillera roads risky.</p>
<p>Solo travel in northern Luzon is the calm introduction to Philippine slow travel. The pace forgives, the people are warm, and the route covers enough variety to keep two weeks interesting.</p>
