    // 34. PAMPANGA FOOD-ONLY CRAWL ONE DAY
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.travelaroundph.com/pampanga-food-trail',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Travel Around Philippines',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Pampanga Food-Only Crawl: A One-Day Plan From Manila',
        'slug' => 'pampanga-food-only-crawl-one-day-plan-manila',
        'excerpt' => 'A food-focused day trip through Pampanga covering sisig, kapampangan kakanin, and the Angeles dessert scene.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Pampanga is the culinary capital of the Philippines and a one-day food crawl from Manila covers four to five regional specialties in under nine hours. This is the food-only plan with no museum stops or theme parks. The crawl runs from breakfast in San Fernando to merienda in Angeles to a late dinner before the drive back.</p>
<p>Pampanga sits two hours from Manila via NLEX. Tara, here is the day by meal.</p>
<h2>Breakfast: Tibok-Tibok and Kapeng Barako</h2>
<p>Start in San Fernando city around eight in the morning. Drop by the Susie's Cuisine outlet at the rotunda for the morning tibok-tibok, a carabao milk pudding topped with toasted latik. Pair with a small cup of kapeng barako. The vendors near the Pampanga Provincial Capitol also sell the local puto-bumbong and bibingka all year, not just in December.</p>
<p>Alternative: drive 10 minutes to Brgy Calulut for the home-style breakfast at one of the small carinderias serving tocino, longganisa, and sinangag with sunny-side eggs.</p>
<h2>Mid-Morning: Aling Lucing Sisig</h2>
<p>Drive to Aling Lucing in Angeles for the original sisig. The place is small, the line forms by 10 in the morning, and the dish is the prototype that every other sisig variant in the Philippines is measured against. Order the sisig manok or sisig baboy with a side of bagoong rice. The chopped pork is grilled fresh; the squeeze of calamansi at the end is the local technique.</p>
<p>If Aling Lucing has a long line, alternatives in Angeles include Mila's Tokwa't Baboy or the small carinderias near the public market.</p>
<h2>Lunch: Bringhe and Kare-Kare</h2>
<p>Drive to one of the heritage Kapampangan restaurants in Angeles or Bacolor for lunch. Atching Lillian Borromeo's home kitchen in Mexico, Pampanga, serves the traditional bringhe, a Kapampangan paella variant with chicken, prawns, and turmeric rice. Reservations are required; the kitchen is small and serves limited covers per day.</p>
<p>Alternative: drive to Apag Marangle in Magalang for the kare-kare and crispy pata. The restaurant sits in a rice paddy setting and the bagoong is house-fermented. Lunch portions are large; one order feeds two.</p>
<h2>Merienda: Halo-Halo and Pichi-Pichi</h2>
<p>Drive to Razon's in Guagua or its Angeles branch for the famous halo-halo. The Pampanga version uses fewer ingredients than the Visayan or Manila version: just sweetened saba banana, leche flan, macapuno, milk, and ice. The minimalism is the point. Pair with a pichi-pichi from the small kakanin vendors near the restaurant.</p>
<p>If Razon's has a long line, the Susie's Cuisine outlets carry a smaller version of the halo-halo and the full range of Kapampangan kakanin.</p>
<h2>Dinner: Crispy Pata and Tapa King Alternatives</h2>
<p>For the evening meal, drive back to San Fernando for one of the heritage restaurants serving full Kapampangan sets. Camalig in Angeles offers a sit-down plate with crispy pata, bringhe, and the regional vegetable sides. The portions are large; one set serves two.</p>
<p>Alternative: drive to one of the small Tapa King outlets near NLEX exit for a quick beef tapa silog before the drive back to Manila. Not the heritage option but a calmer late-evening choice.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Manila, take NLEX to the Dau exit for Angeles or the San Fernando exit for the provincial capital. Travel time is around two hours each way. By bus, Victory Liner and Five Star run buses to Dau and San Fernando every 30 minutes.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>Year-round works for the food crawl. The dry months from December to May make the drive easier. Avoid Holy Week and the December break if you want short lines at the popular places; the diaspora crowd fills the heritage restaurants.</p>
<p>Pampanga is the rare Philippine province where a food-only day plan covers more than enough variety. Skip the theme parks and the day becomes a tour of regional Kapampangan cooking at its source.</p>
