    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 35. VIGAN HERITAGE CHURCH ROUTE WALK
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.travelaroundph.com/vigan-heritage-walk',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Travel Around Philippines',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Vigan Heritage Church Route: A Calm Half-Day Walk',
        'slug' => 'vigan-heritage-church-route-calm-half-day-walk',
        'excerpt' => 'Vigan has more churches than the standard Calle Crisologo tour shows. Here is the slow half-day walk covering four heritage churches.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Vigan is famous for the Calle Crisologo cobblestone street but the heritage city also holds four important churches within walking or short tricycle distance of the plaza. This is the calmer church route, designed as a slow half-day walk that gets you past the calesa tour version of Vigan.</p>
<p>The route starts at the cathedral and ends at the Bantay Bell Tower. Tara, here is the walk by stop.</p>
<h2>Saint Paul Metropolitan Cathedral</h2>
<p>The Vigan Cathedral was built in 1574 and rebuilt several times after earthquakes. The current structure is from the early 19th century, with a plain late baroque facade and twin bell towers. The cathedral is the seat of the Archdiocese of Nueva Segovia, one of the oldest dioceses in the Philippines. Free entry, modest dress, daily mass at six in the morning.</p>
<p>The interior holds a wooden retablo with the original altarpieces and the side chapels of the patron saints. The cathedral plaza in front, known as Plaza Salcedo, is the heart of Vigan and the location of the nightly dancing fountain show.</p>
<h2>Saint Augustine Church (Bantay)</h2>
<p>Bantay sits around 10 minutes by tricycle from the Vigan plaza, across the river. The Saint Augustine Church was built in 1591 and rebuilt several times. The detached bell tower, known as the Bantay Bell Tower, sits on a small hill and served as a watchtower during the Spanish colonial period. The tower has been used as a filming location for several Filipino historical movies.</p>
<p>You can climb the bell tower for a view of the surrounding plain. The climb is around three stories of wooden stairs and the top has a basic wooden floor. The view extends to the Vigan town center, the Abra River, and the foothills of the Cordillera.</p>
<h2>Crisologo Museum and Old Stone Bridge</h2>
<p>On the way back to Vigan from Bantay, stop at the Crisologo Museum near the city plaza. The museum is the home of the assassinated Ilocos Sur governor Floro Crisologo and his wife, Carmeling. The exhibits cover the family history, the political assassination at the cathedral in 1970, and the surrounding colonial period.</p>
<p>The old stone bridge across the Govantes River sits one block south. The bridge is a Spanish-era structure that connects Vigan with Bantay. Walk across for the slow heritage moment.</p>
<h2>Simbaan a Bassit</h2>
<p>The Simbaan a Bassit, also known as the Vigan Cemetery Chapel, sits at the southern edge of the city. The chapel was built in the late 18th century as a funerary chapel and the surrounding cemetery holds graves from the early colonial period. The facade is plain and the interior is small but the historical depth is substantial.</p>
<p>Walk the cemetery for around 20 minutes. The older stone markers and the perimeter wall give you a calmer angle to Vigan than the Calle Crisologo tour.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>The cathedral and the cemetery are walkable from the Vigan plaza. The Bantay church and bell tower require a tricycle ride or a 25-minute walk across the river. By car, the cathedral parking is on Plaza Salcedo.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat</h2>
<p>The carinderias around the Vigan plaza serve early breakfast and rice meals. Vigan longganisa, bagnet, and the local empanada are the regional orders. For a sit-down meal, the heritage restaurants on Calle Crisologo serve traditional Ilocano sets.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through May is the dry window. The Vigan church route is open year-round. Weekday mornings are quietest at the cathedral; weekend mornings get the Sunday mass crowd. The Vigan town fiesta in late January fills the plaza.</p>
<p>Vigan is more than the cobblestone street. Walk the four churches, climb the Bantay tower, and the heritage city gives you a different read than the calesa loop.</p>
