    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 36. PHOTOGRAPHY SUNRISE SPOTS MANILA BAY
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.travelaroundph.com/manila-sunrise-spots',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Travel Around Philippines',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Manila Bay Sunrise Spots: A Photographer Slow Read',
        'slug' => 'manila-bay-sunrise-spots-photographer-slow-read',
        'excerpt' => 'A photography-focused guide to the calmer sunrise spots around Manila Bay, from Mall of Asia to Las Pinas to Cavite coast.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Manila Bay faces west, so the bay itself is the sunset spot. Sunrise photography around Manila, then, requires looking inland or south to the Cavite coast where the bay curves and the morning light catches the eastern horizon. This is a slow read of the calmer sunrise photography spots within a 90-minute drive of central Manila.</p>
<p>The spots are spread along the Manila-Cavite coastal road. Tara, here is the slow morning by stop.</p>
<h2>Mall of Asia Bayside</h2>
<p>The Mall of Asia bayside promenade faces west, so the actual sunrise direction is behind you, looking east toward the city. The light at five thirty in the morning hits the bay water from the side and creates a calm reflection on the still surface. The line of moored boats off the bayside is the foreground subject.</p>
<p>Walk the promenade from the MOA Globe south to the Esplanade for around 30 minutes of slow shooting. The area is busy by seven; arrive by five to have the promenade to yourself. Light traffic and easy parking before six.</p>
<h2>CCP Bayside and Roxas Boulevard</h2>
<p>The CCP Complex bayside promenade is the older Manila sunrise spot. The bay opens west and the light at five thirty hits the harbor cranes and the old buildings of Roxas Boulevard from behind. The reflections on the water are the photographic subject.</p>
<p>Walk south from the CCP toward Sofitel for around 20 minutes. The American war memorial and the Cultural Center sculpture make for foreground subjects. The light improves dramatically by six in the morning.</p>
<h2>Las Pinas and the Cavite Coast</h2>
<p>The bay coast continues south through Las Pinas and into Bacoor and Kawit. The Las Pinas Salt Beds, a working salt evaporation area, sit along the bayside near the Las Pinas-Bacoor boundary. The morning light hits the salt flats from the east at six and the reflections are spectacular when the beds are at full evaporation.</p>
<p>Plan to arrive at the salt beds by five forty. Park along the coastal road and walk down to the embankment. The salt farmers tolerate visitors who do not interrupt the harvest. Around 45 minutes for the slow shoot.</p>
<h2>Kawit and the Old Aguinaldo Pier</h2>
<p>Drive 30 minutes south of the Las Pinas salt beds to Kawit Cavite. The old fishing pier near the Aguinaldo Shrine offers a different angle of the bay. The fishing bancas pull up to the pier from the morning catch and the activity by six creates a working-coast morning scene.</p>
<p>The Aguinaldo Shrine itself opens at eight, but the pier is accessible earlier. Plan around 30 minutes for the pier morning shoot.</p>
<h2>Maragondon and Ternate Sunrise</h2>
<p>If you have a longer morning, drive to Ternate Cavite for the sunrise over the Manila Bay opening. The marine base view point on the hill above Ternate gives you the panoramic east-facing morning shot. The drive from Las Pinas takes around two hours each way.</p>
<h2>Photography Tips</h2>
<p>Bring a tripod for the long exposure shots. The morning light is soft and warm until around six fifteen, then turns harder and brighter. Use a polarizing filter to cut the bay water glare. A wide-angle lens (16 to 24mm) covers the bay panorama best; a 50mm prime works for the foreground details.</p>
<p>Dress in layers; the morning air can be cool from December to February. Bring a flashlight for the early arrival in the dark. The bayside walkways are well-lit but the salt beds and the fishing piers are not.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through February is the dry window and the clearest mornings. The smog is at its lightest after the rains stop. March to May has clearer skies but more haze from the heat. Sunrise time varies from five forty in December to five twenty in June.</p>
<p>Manila Bay sunrise photography rewards the slow photographer who arrives early and walks the coast. Pick one spot per morning, work it patiently, and the bay gives you the calm dawn that the western sunset crowd usually misses.</p>
