    // 37. SUNSET MACTAN CEBU BOARDWALK
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.travelaroundph.com/mactan-sunset',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Travel Around Philippines',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Mactan Cebu Sunset Spots: A Slow Photographer Read',
        'slug' => 'mactan-cebu-sunset-spots-slow-photographer-read',
        'excerpt' => 'A photography-focused guide to Mactan and Cebu City sunset spots from the SRP boardwalk to the Marigondon coast.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Mactan and Cebu City face west across the Cebu Strait toward Negros. The strait creates a clear westward view that gives Mactan one of the better sunset windows in the Visayas. This is a slow photographer read covering five spots from the South Road Properties boardwalk to the Marigondon eastern coast and a few stops in between.</p>
<p>The spots are spread along the Mactan and Cebu coastline. Tara, here is the slow evening by stop.</p>
<h2>SRP Boardwalk and Il Corso</h2>
<p>The South Road Properties (SRP) boardwalk on the southern Cebu City coast faces west and offers an unobstructed sunset view across the strait. The Il Corso lifestyle mall sits at the southern end of the boardwalk and has a clear bay view. The wide concrete promenade is calm in the late afternoon and the few moored fishing bancas make for foreground subjects.</p>
<p>Walk the boardwalk from the SM Seaside to Il Corso for around 30 minutes of slow shooting. The light at five forty in the dry season turns deep orange and reflects on the bay. The crowd is light on weekdays.</p>
<h2>Mactan Newtown Beach</h2>
<p>Mactan Newtown sits on the eastern coast of Mactan Island and has a small white-sand beach with a calm promenade. The sunset direction is technically west but the development orientation lets you shoot the western horizon across the open sea. The beach is small and the view is partially blocked by the resort row, but the angle works for the late-evening last-light shots.</p>
<p>Walk the beach for around 20 minutes. Parking and the entry to the beach require day passes from the Mactan Newtown management.</p>
<h2>Mactan Marigondon Coast</h2>
<p>The Marigondon coast on the eastern side of Mactan offers a different angle. The sunset over the western horizon is blocked by the island ridge, but the early evening light hits the coast from the side and creates calm color in the eastern sky. The Marigondon beachfront promenade is quiet on weekdays.</p>
<p>Walk the promenade from the public beach to the small fishing harbor for around 30 minutes. The fishing bancas in the harbor make for foreground subjects.</p>
<h2>Punta Engano Cape</h2>
<p>The Punta Engano cape sits at the northern tip of Mactan, near the resort area. The cape juts west into the strait and offers one of the few unobstructed sunset views on the island. The walk along the cape requires day-pass access through the surrounding resorts, but the public road near the lighthouse is accessible.</p>
<p>Plan around 45 minutes at the cape for the slow shoot. The lighthouse foundation and the small rock formations along the shore are the foreground subjects.</p>
<h2>Cebu Capitol and the City Skyline</h2>
<p>For a city-side sunset, drive to the elevated viewpoint near the Cebu Provincial Capitol. The angle gives you the city skyline silhouette against the western sky. The light is best around six in the dry season.</p>
<p>Park on Osmena Boulevard and walk to the viewpoint. The capitol grounds close by six but the boulevard is accessible later. Around 20 minutes for the slow shoot.</p>
<h2>Photography Tips</h2>
<p>Bring a tripod for the long exposures. Use a polarizing filter to cut the water glare. Wide-angle lenses (16 to 24mm) capture the panorama; 50mm primes work for the city silhouette and the fishing boat foregrounds. A graduated ND filter helps balance the sky and the bay water.</p>
<p>Dress in light cotton; the Cebu evenings are warm year-round. Bring water and a small snack; the boardwalk and the coastal promenades have limited vendor stalls past six.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through May is the dry window with the clearest skies. The wet months from June to October have more cloud cover that creates dramatic sunset color but unpredictable conditions. Sunset time runs from five forty in December to six fifteen in June.</p>
<p>Mactan and Cebu City sunset photography rewards the photographer who works one spot patiently. Pick the SRP boardwalk for the unobstructed bay view or Mactan Newtown for the resort-coast read, and the late hour becomes the calm photographic close of the day.</p>
