    // 38. HERITAGE CHURCH ROUTE ILOCOS SUR
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.travelaroundph.com/ilocos-sur-churches',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Travel Around Philippines',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Ilocos Sur Church Route: A Slow Heritage Drive',
        'slug' => 'ilocos-sur-church-route-slow-heritage-drive',
        'excerpt' => 'Ilocos Sur has more colonial churches than the Vigan core. Here is the slow drive plan covering Santa Maria, Magsingal, and Cabugao.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Ilocos Sur is the heritage province of the north and Vigan is the centerpiece. The province has more colonial churches than the Vigan core, though, and a slow drive south to Santa Maria and north to Magsingal and Cabugao covers four UNESCO and important provincial churches within a single day. This is the slow heritage drive plan.</p>
<p>The route starts in Vigan and runs south then north. Tara, here is the drive by stop.</p>
<h2>Santa Maria Church (UNESCO)</h2>
<p>Santa Maria is around 45 minutes south of Vigan by car. The Nuestra Senora de la Asuncion Church was built in 1765 and declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1993 as part of the Baroque Churches of the Philippines. The church sits on a small hill above the town, accessed by a long stone staircase from the plaza below. The fortress-style architecture was designed to double as a defense structure.</p>
<p>The facade is plain late baroque with a single bell tower detached from the main church. Free entry, modest dress, weekday mass at six in the morning. The view from the hilltop opens to the surrounding plain and the South China Sea coast.</p>
<h2>Magsingal Church</h2>
<p>Drive north from Vigan to Magsingal, around 30 minutes. The San Guillermo Parish was built in 1827 with a plain late baroque facade and a detached bell tower. The interior holds a wooden retablo with the original altarpieces. Free entry, modest dress.</p>
<p>The Magsingal Museum next to the church houses a collection of Ilocano artifacts and period religious items. Free entry. Allot 30 minutes for the church and the museum.</p>
<h2>Cabugao Church</h2>
<p>Continue north to Cabugao, around 15 minutes from Magsingal. The Saint Mark the Evangelist Parish was built in 1771 and rebuilt in the 19th century. The facade is plain colonial with a single bell tower. The plaza in front is one of the more spacious in Ilocos Sur.</p>
<p>The church survived the 1983 earthquake and the original interior remains. Free entry, modest dress. Plan around 20 minutes for the visit.</p>
<h2>Sinait Church</h2>
<p>Drive further north to Sinait, around 20 minutes from Cabugao. The Santo Nino Parish was built in 1654 and houses the venerated image of the Holy Child of Sinait, which according to local lore arrived by sea in a wooden chest. The church is a Marian pilgrimage site and the second Sunday of May feast day draws thousands.</p>
<p>The facade is plain late baroque with a single bell tower. The interior is darker than the Vigan churches and the image of the Santo Nino is enshrined behind a glass case in the side chapel. Free entry, modest dress.</p>
<h2>Back to Vigan: Bantay Bell Tower</h2>
<p>End the route at the Bantay Bell Tower near Vigan for the late afternoon light. The tower sits on a small hill and the climb gives you a view of the surrounding plain. The Saint Augustine Church at the base was built in 1591.</p>
<p>Allot 45 minutes for the climb and the church. The tower closes by five in the afternoon.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Vigan, the drive south to Santa Maria takes 45 minutes via the Manila North Road. North to Magsingal, Cabugao, and Sinait takes around 90 minutes total. By bus, the route is doable but slow; rent a car or hire a van for the day.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat</h2>
<p>The carinderias around each town plaza serve early breakfast and rice meals. Ilocos longganisa, bagnet, and the local empanada are the regional orders. For a sit-down lunch, return to Vigan for the heritage restaurants on Calle Crisologo.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through May is the dry window. The churches are open year-round. Weekday mornings are quietest. The Sinait Santo Nino feast in May draws the largest crowd of the year; visit on a different day if you want quiet churches.</p>
<p>Ilocos Sur has a deeper heritage layer than the Vigan core. Drive the church route, climb the towers, and the province gives you a wider read of the Spanish colonial north.</p>
