    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 39. ILOILO FOOD TRAIL BEYOND LA PAZ BATCHOY
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.travelaroundph.com/iloilo-food-trail',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Travel Around Philippines',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Iloilo Food Trail Beyond La Paz Batchoy',
        'slug' => 'iloilo-food-trail-beyond-la-paz-batchoy',
        'excerpt' => 'Iloilo has more than batchoy. Here is the slow food trail covering chicken inasal, KBL, pancit Molo, and Iloilo dessert stops.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Iloilo City is famous for the La Paz batchoy, but the regional food scene runs much deeper. This is a slow food trail covering five other dishes beyond the batchoy bowl: chicken inasal, KBL (kadyos-baboy-langka), pancit Molo, the original Iloilo empanada, and the local Iloilo desserts. The trail runs one full day from breakfast to dinner.</p>
<p>The stops are spread across the city center. Tara, here is the day by meal.</p>
<h2>Breakfast: Pancit Molo</h2>
<p>Start the day in the Molo district. The pancit Molo is a wonton soup made with pork-and-shrimp dumplings in a clear broth, originally from the Molo Chinese community. The dish is the breakfast staple of the district. Order at one of the small carinderias near the Molo Plaza or the historic Molo Church.</p>
<p>Pair with a small cup of barako coffee. The Molo bakery near the church sells fresh pandesal and the local biscocho for take-away. Plan around 60 minutes for the meal and a short walk through the plaza.</p>
<h2>Mid-Morning: Iloilo Empanada</h2>
<p>Drive 15 minutes from Molo to the Calle Real heritage district. The original Iloilo empanada is a small fried turnover filled with chicken and chayote, smaller and crispier than the Vigan version. The vendors on Calle Real and the small panaderias near the Iloilo plaza sell the freshest batches mid-morning.</p>
<p>Pair with the local salabat (ginger tea) or hot chocolate from one of the heritage cafes on Calle Real. Plan around 30 minutes for the merienda stop.</p>
<h2>Lunch: KBL (Kadyos-Baboy-Langka)</h2>
<p>Drive to one of the heritage Ilonggo restaurants for KBL, the regional pork-and-vegetable stew with kadyos (pigeon peas), baboy (pork), and langka (young jackfruit). The dish is the Sunday lunch of the Ilonggo household and the local restaurants like Tatoy's Manokan and Camina Balay nga Bato serve the heritage versions.</p>
<p>Order with rice and a side of grilled tilapia. The KBL portions are large; one order feeds two. Plan around 90 minutes for the sit-down lunch.</p>
<h2>Mid-Afternoon: Chicken Inasal</h2>
<p>Drive to the Inasal Manokan country in the Diversion Road area for late lunch or early dinner. Chicken inasal is the Ilonggo version of grilled chicken, marinated in calamansi, garlic, and pepper, basted with annatto oil. The Bacolod version gets more press but the Iloilo version is older.</p>
<p>Order pecho or paa with rice, sinamak (spiced vinegar), and a side of garlic. The portions are sized for two. Plan around 60 minutes.</p>
<h2>Merienda: La Paz Batchoy</h2>
<p>You cannot do an Iloilo food trail without the batchoy. Drive to Ted's, Deco's, or Netong's in the La Paz district for the original noodle soup. The broth is pork-based with chicharon, liver, and meat slices, served over miki noodles. The recipe is unchanged since the early 20th century.</p>
<p>Order the small bowl if you have already had lunch. Plan around 45 minutes for the merienda stop.</p>
<h2>Evening: Biscocho and the Iloilo Dessert Trail</h2>
<p>End the day at one of the heritage bakeries on Calle Real for the local sweets. Biscocho de Iloilo is a twice-baked bread brushed with butter and sugar, sold in large sheets. Pair with hot chocolate or coffee. The Original Biscocho Haus near the city center sells the well-known version.</p>
<p>The barquillos and the pinipig wafers are the other Iloilo dessert standards. Buy a few boxes to bring home.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Manila, fly to Iloilo in one hour fifteen minutes. The food trail is doable in a single day with a car or a series of tricycles. Allot a full day for the slow pace.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>Year-round works for the food trail. The dry months from December to May make the walking and the al fresco dining easier. The Dinagyang Festival in late January is the headline event; food queues are longer then.</p>
<p>Iloilo is the Visayan food capital that does not market itself as one. Skip the batchoy-only itinerary and the city gives you a full regional cuisine in a calm day.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Iloilo Food Trail Beyond La Paz Batchoy | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A one-day Iloilo food trail covering pancit Molo, empanada, KBL, chicken inasal, batchoy, and biscocho. Practical stops from Molo to Calle Real.',
