    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.travelaroundph.com/antipolo-couple-weekend',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Travel Around Philippines',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Antipolo Couple Weekend: A Calm Cafe and Chapel Plan',
        'slug' => 'antipolo-couple-weekend-calm-cafe-chapel-plan',
        'excerpt' => 'A slow Antipolo couple weekend plan covering the cathedral, the cliffside cafes, and the Pinto Art Museum.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Antipolo sits on a ridge east of Manila, around 90 minutes from Quezon City via Marcos Highway. The city is one of the closer couple weekends to Manila, with a Marian cathedral, cliffside cafes, and the Pinto Art Museum within a single morning loop. This is the slow plan for the calmer Antipolo couple angle.</p>
<p>The city center sits along the Sumulong Highway. Tara, here is the weekend by day.</p>
<h2>Day One: Cathedral and Sunset</h2>
<p>The Antipolo Cathedral is the home of the Our Lady of Peace and Good Voyage, the patroness of the city and one of the older Marian pilgrimage images in the Philippines. The image was brought from Mexico in 1626 and the cathedral is the main shrine. The current structure is a large modern church with a wide plaza in front.</p>
<p>Couples often light a candle at the shrine before the rest of the day. Free entry, modest dress, weekday mass at six in the morning. Allot 30 minutes for the cathedral visit.</p>
<p>After the cathedral, drive to one of the cliffside cafes along Sumulong Highway for late lunch and the sunset. Burrow Cafe, Cafe Lupe, and Crescent Moon Cafe are the calmer options with western-facing terraces. The sunset over the Metro Manila skyline is the photographic moment of the weekend.</p>
<h2>Day Two: Pinto Art Museum</h2>
<p>Pinto Art Museum sits on Sierra Madre Hills, a 15-minute drive east of the cathedral. The museum is a series of white Mediterranean-style buildings holding contemporary Philippine art across several galleries. The grounds include a chapel, a garden, and several outdoor sculptures.</p>
<p>Plan around three hours for the slow walk through the galleries. The grounds are large and the architecture is photogenic for couple shots. The chapel inside the museum is small and quiet. Entry fees are moderate.</p>
<h2>Day Two Afternoon: Hinulugang Taktak</h2>
<p>Drive 20 minutes from Pinto to Hinulugang Taktak, the Antipolo waterfall and the inspiration for the local folk song. The falls have been restored as a small park with a viewing deck and a swimming area. The water flow is reduced from the historical level but the site retains its calm folk-song character.</p>
<p>Walk the park for around 45 minutes. The viewing deck offers a clean look at the falls; the swimming area is open seasonally.</p>
<h2>Day Two Late Afternoon: Cafe at Mt. Purro</h2>
<p>End the weekend at Mt. Purro Nature Reserve, around 30 minutes east of Hinulugang Taktak. The reserve is a small private property with a cafe, a chapel, and a few short walking trails through a reforested area. The setting is one of the calmer couple stops near Antipolo.</p>
<p>Plan around 90 minutes for the cafe and a short walk. Entry fees are modest and the cafe serves brewed coffee, pasta, and local desserts.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>The Antipolo accommodation scene includes a few small bed and breakfasts along Sumulong Highway and a couple of larger hotels in the city center. The cliffside cafes do not have lodging; you stay in the city center and drive to the cafes. Day trips from Manila are also doable if you skip the overnight.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Quezon City, drive via Marcos Highway through Cogeo and into Antipolo. Travel time is around 90 minutes. By public transport, take a UV Express van from Cubao bound for Antipolo. Tricycles cover the city center.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat</h2>
<p>The cliffside cafes along Sumulong Highway serve full meals. For traditional Antipolo dishes, drive to the city center for the suman, kasoy, and the local longganisa. The carinderias near the cathedral serve early breakfast and rice meals.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through February is the cool dry window and the most comfortable for the cliffside terraces. The wet months from June to October have more cloud cover but the morning fog over the cathedral can be photogenic. Weekday couples have the calmer experience.</p>
<p>Antipolo is the rare Manila weekend that combines a Marian shrine, contemporary art, and cliffside cafes in a single 24-hour loop. Pick the slow stops and the city gives you a calmer couple weekend than the standard Tagaytay drive.</p>
